reason: ABCB1 encodes a well-characterized ABC transporter known as P-glycoprotein, involved in multidrug resistance.
ABCC1 encodes the MRP1 protein, another ABC transporter involved in multidrug resistance and organic anion transport.
ABCG2 encodes the Breast Cancer Resistance Protein (BCRP), an ABC transporter that affects drug distribution and excretion.
ABCA1 encodes a transporter involved in cholesterol and phospholipid transport, playing a critical role in lipid homeostasis.
ABCB4 encodes a phospholipid transporter essential for bile formation and liver function.
ABCB11 encodes the bile salt export pump, which is critical for bile salt secretion into the bile canaliculi.
ABCC2 encodes MRP2, an ABC transporter involved in excreting organic anions and drugs into bile and urine.
ABCC3 encodes MRP3, an ABC transporter that moves organic anions from cells into the blood.
ABCC4 encodes MRP4, which is involved in the transport of nucleoside analogs and other drugs.
ABCC5 encodes MRP5, a transporter of cyclic nucleotides and nucleotide analogs.
ABCG1 encodes a transporter involved in cholesterol and phospholipid efflux to high-density lipoproteins (HDL).
ABCA4 encodes a transporter involved in the visual cycle, specifically in the transport of retinal derivatives.
ABCB2 encodes a transporter involved in antigen processing and presentation through the Major Histocompatibility Complex (MHC) class I pathway.
ABCB3 encodes another transporter involved in antigen processing and presentation, working alongside ABCB2.
TAP1 encodes a transporter associated with antigen processing, a critical component of the immune response.
TAP2 encodes a component of the transporter associated with antigen processing, which transports antigenic peptides into the endoplasmic reticulum.
AGER encodes the receptor for advanced glycation end-products (RAGE), a key player in the AGE-RAGE signaling pathway.
HSPB1 is upregulated in response to AGE-RAGE interaction, influencing oxidative stress and inflammation.
NFKB1 is a central transcription factor activated by the AGE-RAGE signaling, leading to the expression of various inflammatory genes.
MAPK14 (p38 MAPK) mediates downstream signaling in the AGE-RAGE pathway, affecting inflammation and cellular stress responses.
RELA, a component of NF-κB, is essential for mediating AGE-RAGE-induced transcription of pro-inflammatory cytokines.
TNF is a cytokine whose expression is elevated via the AGE-RAGE pathway, exacerbating inflammatory responses.
IL6 is a pro-inflammatory cytokine upregulated by the AGE-RAGE signaling cascade.
VEGFA is involved in angiogenesis and is upregulated as a part of the inflammatory response in the AGE-RAGE pathway.
FOXO1 regulates genes involved in oxidative stress and is modulated by the AGE-RAGE pathway.
TGFBR1 plays a role in the AGE-RAGE-mediated fibrosis and tissue remodeling processes.
NOX4 contributes to the production of reactive oxygen species (ROS) in response to AGE-RAGE interaction.
PTEN is a negative regulator of the PI3K/AKT pathway, which is modulated downstream of AGE-RAGE signaling.
PLAUR is involved in extracellular matrix remodeling and is influenced by the AGE-RAGE signaling pathway.
PRKAA1 encodes the alpha-1 catalytic subunit of AMPK, which is a central enzyme in the AMPK signaling pathway.
PRKAA2 encodes the alpha-2 catalytic subunit of AMPK, another catalytic core enzyme in the AMPK signaling pathway.
PRKAB1 encodes the beta-1 regulatory subunit of AMPK, which regulates the activity of the AMPK complex.
PRKAB2 encodes the beta-2 regulatory subunit of AMPK, which plays a role in stabilizing and regulating AMPK.
PRKAG1 encodes the gamma-1 regulatory subunit of AMPK, important for AMP binding and AMPK activity.
PRKAG2 encodes the gamma-2 regulatory subunit of AMPK, crucial for regulation by cellular energy levels.
PRKAG3 encodes the gamma-3 regulatory subunit of AMPK, which also contributes to the regulation by AMP.
LKB1 encodes a kinase that phosphorylates AMPK, activating it in response to metabolic stress.
CAMKK2 encodes calcium/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase kinase 2, which can phosphorylate and activate AMPK.
MTOR is a downstream target of the AMPK signaling pathway and its inhibition by AMPK regulates cell growth.
PPARGC1A encodes a transcription coactivator that is regulated by AMPK and important for mitochondrial biogenesis.
SIRT1 is an upstream regulator of AMPK, influencing its activation through deacetylation.
TSC2 is involved in the AMPK signaling pathway by integrating signals to inhibit the mTOR pathway, a downstream target.
FOXO3 is regulated by AMPK and plays a role in the transcription of genes involved in oxidative stress resistance.
ULK1 is activated by AMPK and involved in initiating autophagy in response to low energy conditions.
AKT1 negatively regulates AMPK activity by phosphorylation in response to insulin signaling.
RUNX1 mutations are commonly associated with the development and progression of acute myeloid leukemia.
NPM1 mutations, particularly the NPM1c+ variant, are frequently found in acute myeloid leukemia patients.
FLT3 internal tandem duplications and point mutations lead to constitutive activation of the receptor tyrosine kinase in acute myeloid leukemia.
Mutations in CEBPA are implicated in altering myeloid differentiation and are common in acute myeloid leukemia.
Mutations and deletions in TP53 are often linked to poor prognosis in acute myeloid leukemia.
IDH1 mutations result in the production of an oncometabolite implicated in the pathogenesis of acute myeloid leukemia.
IDH2 mutations also lead to the production of an oncometabolite, contributing to leukemogenesis in acute myeloid leukemia.
Mutations in DNMT3A are known to impact DNA methylation patterns and are frequently observed in acute myeloid leukemia.
Mutations in KIT, particularly in core-binding factor leukemias, are associated with increased proliferation and poor outcome in acute myeloid leukemia.
WT1 mutations and overexpression are frequently found in acute myeloid leukemia and correlate with disease progression.
TET2 mutations affect hematopoietic stem cell function and are recurrently found in patients with acute myeloid leukemia.
ASXL1 mutations are implicated in myeloid transformation and are common in acute myeloid leukemia patients.
Mixed-lineage leukemia (MLL) gene translocations and mutations are often associated with acute myeloid leukemia.
Overexpression of EVI1, often due to 3q26 rearrangements, is linked to poor prognosis in acute myeloid leukemia.

Encodes elongation of very long chain fatty acids protein 5, which is implicated in the elongation of polyunsaturated fatty acids including arachidonic acid.
Encodes cytochrome P450 4A11, which is involved in the ω-hydroxylation of arachidonic acid.
Encodes prostaglandin D synthase, which is involved in the conversion of prostaglandin H2 to prostaglandin D2.

Encodes for ornithine aminotransferase, important in the conversion of ornithine to proline.
Encodes for aldehyde dehydrogenase 4 family member A1, involved in the conversion of delta-1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate to glutamate.
Encodes for prolyl 4-hydroxylase subunit alpha 1 which is involved in the hydroxylation of proline residues in collagen.
Encodes for neuronal nitric oxide synthase, which converts arginine into nitric oxide and citrulline.

Encodes for spermidine/spermine N1-acetyltransferase 1, involved in the catabolism of polyamines derived from arginine.
Encodes for adenylate cyclase 7, indirectly related as it influences cAMP levels which can regulate enzymes involved in arginine metabolism.
Encodes for pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase 1, which converts pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline.
Encodes for pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase 2, an isoform involved in converting pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline.
Encodes for pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase 3, another isoform involved in converting pyrroline-5-carboxylate to proline.
Encodes for glycine amidinotransferase, which catalyzes the rate-limiting step in creatine synthesis from arginine and glycine.
Encodes for agmatinase, an enzyme that converts agmatine, a product of arginine decarboxylation, to putrescine.

ASL encodes argininosuccinate lyase, which is involved in the conversion of argininosuccinate to arginine and fumarate in one of the final steps of arginine biosynthesis.

OTC encodes ornithine transcarbamylase, which catalyzes the reaction between carbamoyl phosphate and ornithine to form citrulline, an intermediate in arginine biosynthesis.

Mutations in this gene encoding plakophilin-2 are the most common cause of arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
This gene encodes desmoplakin, a crucial component of desmosomes, and mutations are linked to arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
Desmoglein-2 mutations disrupt cell adhesion, contributing to arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
Mutations in desmocollin-2, a cadherin family protein, are implicated in arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
Junction plakoglobin is a key component of desmosomes, and its mutations are associated with arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
The gene encodes for a transmembrane protein involved in nuclear-cytoskeletal connections, and its mutations are linked to arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
Mutations in lamin A/C are known to cause a variety of cardiomyopathies, including arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
This gene encodes alpha-T-catenin, and mutations can lead to arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy by disrupting cell adhesion.
Catenin beta-1 mutations can indirectly affect cell adhesion and signaling pathways involved in arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy.
GULO encodes for L-gulonolactone oxidase, an enzyme crucial in the biosynthesis of ascorbate (vitamin C).
HK1 encodes hexokinase 1, which catalyzes the phosphorylation of glucose to glucose-6-phosphate, a key intermediate in glycolysis and related metabolic pathways, including ascorbate metabolism.
AKR1A1 encodes aldehyde reductase, which is known to reduce aldoses and aldehydes involved in aldarate metabolism.
AKR1B1 encodes aldose reductase, an enzyme involved in the reduction of glucose to sorbitol, indirectly affecting ascorbate metabolism through the polyol pathway.
IDH1 encodes isocitrate dehydrogenase 1, an enzyme that converts isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate, which plays a role in the cellular redox state affecting ascorbate metabolism.

GLRX encodes glutaredoxin, which is involved in redox regulation within cells, impacting the redox balance necessary for ascorbate recycling.
MDH1 encodes malate dehydrogenase 1, which participates in the malate-aspartate shuttle that influences cellular NAD+/NADH balance and ascorbate metabolism.
SORD encodes sorbitol dehydrogenase, which converts sorbitol to fructose, an important intermediate in the aldarate metabolism pathway.
Encodes a cytokine involved in the differentiation of naive helper T cells (Th0) to Th2 cells, which play a critical role in the pathogenesis of asthma.
Encodes a cytokine that is important in the regulation of inflammatory and immune responses, often overexpressed in asthma patients.
Associated with airway remodeling and hyperresponsiveness in asthma.
Linked to childhood asthma and thought to regulate calcium homeostasis in the endoplasmic reticulum.
Encodes a cytokine that promotes the growth and activation of eosinophils, which are commonly elevated in asthma patients.
Encodes the IL-33 receptor, which is involved in the immune response and inflammation seen in asthma.
Encodes a cytokine involved in the pathogenesis of asthma through promotion of neutrophilic inflammation.
Associated with inflammatory processes and airway hyperresponsiveness in asthma.
Linked with the regulation of epithelial cell apoptosis and associated with asthma susceptibility.
Associated with lung function and the risk of developing asthma.

HLA-DRB1 is involved in antigen presentation and is associated with increased susceptibility to autoimmune thyroid diseases.
CTLA4 encodes a protein that acts as an immune checkpoint and is linked to the regulation of autoimmunity, including thyroid disorders.

CD40 is involved in B cell activation and antibody production, and polymorphisms in this gene are linked to autoimmune thyroid disease.
CD25, also known as IL2RA, plays a role in immune response regulation and has been linked to susceptibility to multiple autoimmune diseases including autoimmune thyroid disease.
ATG5 is essential for the elongation of the autophagosomal membrane.
ATG7 functions as an E1-like enzyme essential for autophagy.
BECN1 is critical for the initiation of autophagosome formation.

ULK1 is a kinase that initiates autophagosome formation.
WIPI1 is involved in the formation of autophagosome precursors.
GABARAP is a protein that assists in the elongation of autophagosomes.

NRBF2 interacts with the Class III PI3K complex involved in autophagy regulation.
RAB7A is required for the maturation of autophagosomes.

ATG16L1 forms a complex with ATG12-ATG5 required for autophagosome membrane elongation.
ROBO1 is a receptor for SLIT proteins, which are critical for the repulsive guidance of axons.

NRP1 serves as a co-receptor for class 3 semaphorins, which are critical for axonal guidance.

SEMA3A is a semaphorin that acts as a repellent signal in axon guidance.

L1CAM encodes a cell adhesion molecule important for neuron-neuron adhesion and guidance of growing axons.
NAV2 is involved in neuronal development and axonal guidance through its role in microtubule dynamics.
AGAP2 regulates actin cytoskeleton dynamics and is involved in processes related to axon guidance.
NTN1 encodes the Netrin-1 protein, which is a major cue in axonal guidance pathways.

Encodes Bruton tyrosine kinase essential for downstream signaling of the B cell receptor.
Encodes B cell linker protein, which acts as an adaptor, linking B cell receptor to downstream signaling pathways.
Encodes a component of the B cell receptor complex necessary for signal transduction upon antigen binding.

Encodes a pro-apoptotic protein regulated by B cell receptor signaling to balance cell survival and death.
Encodes a key kinase involved in cell growth and metabolism, activated downstream of B cell receptor signaling pathways.
Encodes a transcription factor activated by B cell receptor signaling to induce expression of survival and proliferation genes.
IL8 is involved in the recruitment of neutrophils to sites of infection, which is crucial during bacterial invasion of epithelial cells.
ICAM1 facilitates the adhesion and transmigration of leukocytes across the endothelium, playing a role in the immune response to bacterial invasion.
TLR4 recognizes lipopolysaccharides on the surface of Gram-negative bacteria, initiating signaling cascades that lead to the innate immune response.
MUC1 is a mucin that serves as a barrier on epithelial surfaces and can interact with bacterial adhesins to prevent infection.
CDH1 encodes E-cadherin, which maintains epithelial integrity and its cleavage or dysfunction can facilitate bacterial invasion.
VIM encodes vimentin which can be exploited by bacteria for cellular invasion by interacting with bacterial proteins.
CLDN1 encodes claudin-1, a tight junction protein that bacteria can target to disrupt epithelial barriers for invasion.
TNF is a cytokine that is elevated during infection and inflammation, playing a role in the immune response to bacterial invasion.
CXCL1 is involved in the recruitment of neutrophils to the site of infection, contributing to the immune defense against bacterial invasion.
CTNNB1 encodes beta-catenin, which plays a role in cell-cell adhesion and signaling pathways that may be manipulated during bacterial invasion.
Mutations in PTCH1 are a common cause of basal cell carcinoma due to its role in the Hedgehog signaling pathway.
SMO mutations activate the Hedgehog signaling pathway, contributing to the development of basal cell carcinoma.

CDKN2A encodes proteins that are crucial for cell cycle regulation and its mutations are associated with basal cell carcinoma.

APE1 encodes an enzyme that incises the DNA backbone at apurinic/apyrimidinic sites created during base excision repair.

ABCC2 encodes the multidrug resistance-associated protein 2 (MRP2), which is responsible for the secretion of organic anions into bile.
SLC10A1 encodes the sodium-taurocholate co-transporting polypeptide (NTCP) that is crucial for the uptake of bile acids from the blood into hepatocytes.

ATP8B1 encodes a flippase involved in maintaining phospholipid asymmetry in the canalicular membrane, important for bile salt secretion.
CFTR encodes the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator, which facilitates chloride and bicarbonate secretion in the bile duct.
TJP2 encodes tight junction protein 2, which is important for maintaining the integrity of the bile duct epithelium.
NR0B2 encodes the small heterodimer partner (SHP), a transcriptional regulator that modulates FXR activation and bile acid synthesis.

Mutations in TP53 are frequently associated with the development and progression of bladder cancer.
Activating mutations in FGFR3 are commonly found in low-grade, non-muscle invasive bladder cancers.
Loss of function mutations in RB1 are linked to high-grade bladder cancer and poor prognosis.
HRAS mutations can lead to abnormal cell signaling pathways, contributing to bladder cancer development.
PIK3CA mutations are involved in the PI3K/AKT pathway, which plays a role in bladder cancer cell proliferation and survival.
Mutations in TSC1 are commonly found in bladder cancer and may contribute to tumor growth through mTOR signaling dysregulation.
Mutations in KMT2D, a histone methyltransferase, are associated with chromatin remodeling defects in bladder cancer.
Deletions or inactivation of CDKN2A are frequently observed in bladder cancer, leading to loss of cell cycle regulation.
Amplification or overexpression of ERBB2 (HER2) is found in a subset of bladder cancers, driving tumorigenesis.
Overexpression of E2F3, involved in cell cycle progression, is common in bladder cancer, promoting uncontrolled cell division.
MDM2 amplification can lead to inactivation of TP53, contributing to the development of bladder cancer.
Mutations in ARID1A, a chromatin remodeling gene, are frequently associated with bladder cancer.
Mutations in the TERT promoter region are commonly found in bladder cancer, leading to increased telomerase activity.
Mutations in NFE2L2 can enhance oxidative stress response pathways, contributing to bladder cancer proliferation.
Loss-of-function mutations in STAG2 are linked to chromosomal instability in bladder cancer.
Mutations in BRCA1 significantly increase the risk of developing breast cancer due to its role in DNA repair.
BRCA2 is involved in DNA repair, and mutations in this gene are also strongly linked to a higher risk of breast cancer.
TP53, often mutated in breast cancer, encodes the p53 protein which acts as a tumor suppressor by regulating cell cycle and apoptosis.
ERBB2, also known as HER2, is frequently amplified in breast cancer, leading to aggressive tumor growth.
The PGR gene encodes the progesterone receptor, and its expression is used to determine hormone receptor status in breast cancer.
ESR1 encodes the estrogen receptor alpha, which is crucial in the development and progression of hormone-dependent breast cancers.
Mutations or loss of the tumor suppressor gene PTEN are associated with breast cancers and contribute to uncontrolled cell growth.
PIK3CA, often mutated in breast cancer, encodes a subunit of PI3K involved in cell growth and survival signaling.
AKT1 is part of the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway and its dysregulation is linked to breast cancer development and progression.
ATM gene mutations are linked to increased breast cancer risk due to its role in DNA damage response.
CHEK2 mutations increase susceptibility to breast cancer by impairing DNA damage checkpoint control.
Loss of CDH1, which encodes the cell adhesion protein E-cadherin, is often observed in lobular breast cancers.
Overexpression of EGFR, a member of the epidermal growth factor receptor family, is involved in the progression of certain breast cancers.
BARD1 interacts with BRCA1 and is involved in DNA repair processes critical to preventing breast cancer.

Encodes a transcription factor that plays a role in cell cycle progression, apoptosis, and cellular transformation.
Encodes a transcription factor that is crucial for the control of the cell cycle and action of tumor suppressor proteins.
Encodes p21, which inhibits cyclin-CDK2 or -CDK4 complexes, and thus functions as a regulator of cell cycle progression at G1.
Encodes p16, which inhibits CDKs 4 and 6, preventing the cell cycle progression from G1 phase to S phase.
Encodes a protein kinase that is activated by DNA damage and initiates a signal transduction cascade leading to cell cycle arrest, DNA repair, or apoptosis.
Encodes a kinase that is involved in the cell cycle checkpoint by halting the cell cycle in response to DNA damage.
Plays a vital role in the initiation of DNA replication and ensures that DNA replication occurs only once per cell cycle.
Encodes a protein that is essential for the initiation and elongation of DNA replication.
CDKN2A encodes p16INK4a, a crucial regulator of cellular senescence through the inhibition of CDK4/6.
TP53 encodes p53, a key tumor suppressor that induces cellular senescence in response to DNA damage and stress.
CDKN1A encodes p21, which is activated by p53 to inhibit cell cycle progression and promote senescence.
RB1 encodes the retinoblastoma protein (RB), which is essential for the maintenance of cellular senescence by regulating E2F transcription factors.
MTOR is involved in the regulation of autophagy and cellular metabolism, processes that are crucial for the development of cellular senescence.
PIK3CA is part of the PI3K/AKT pathway, which influences cell growth and survival and is implicated in the induction of cellular senescence.
TERT encodes the catalytic subunit of telomerase; its downregulation leads to telomere shortening and cellular senescence.
LMNB1 downregulation is associated with the formation of senescence-associated heterochromatic foci, marking the senescent state.
IGFBP7 mediates cellular senescence through the regulation of the insulin-like growth factor pathway.
SIRT1 is involved in the deacetylation of p53 and other targets, modulating pathways related to cellular senescence.
SMAD3 is a key mediator of TGF-β signaling, which plays a role in the induction of cellular senescence.
EZH2 is a component of the PRC2 complex that modulates histone methylation, influencing cellular senescence by regulating the expression of senescence-associated genes.
PDCD4 inhibits translation and is implicated in cellular senescence by controlling the expression of senescence-related pathways.
GADD45A is induced by stress signals and is involved in the stress response that can lead to cellular senescence.
MAPK14 encodes p38 MAPK, which is activated under stress conditions and is crucial for the induction of cellular senescence.
Hexokinase 2 (HK2) catalyzes the first step of glycolysis, often upregulated in cancer cells to meet energy demands.
Pyruvate kinase M1/2 (PKM) regulates the final step in glycolysis, with its M2 isoform frequently expressed in tumors.
Lactate dehydrogenase A (LDHA) converts pyruvate to lactate, a key step in the Warburg effect observed in many cancers.
Isocitrate dehydrogenase 1 (IDH1) participates in the citric acid cycle and its mutations are common in gliomas.
Isocitrate dehydrogenase 2 (IDH2) is involved in the citric acid cycle within mitochondria, with mutations found in various cancers.
Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) is pivotal in the pentose phosphate pathway, providing reducing power and ribose for nucleotide synthesis.
Tumor protein p53 (TP53) regulates numerous genes involved in metabolic processes, apoptosis, and DNA repair, commonly mutated in cancers.
MYC proto-oncogene plays a crucial role in cell growth and metabolism by regulating glycolytic enzymes and mitochondrial biogenesis.
Hypoxia-inducible factor 1-alpha (HIF1A) supports glycolysis under low oxygen levels, often upregulated in tumors to adapt to hypoxic conditions.
Solute carrier family 2 member 1 (SLC2A1) encodes for GLUT1, a glucose transporter upregulated in many cancers to enhance glucose uptake.
Pyruvate dehydrogenase kinase 1 (PDK1) inhibits the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex, promoting glycolysis over oxidative phosphorylation in cancer cells.
ATP citrate lyase (ACLY) links glucose metabolism to lipid biosynthesis, necessary for rapid cell proliferation in cancer.
Phosphofructokinase-1 (PFK1) is a key glycolytic enzyme allosterically regulated by signaling pathways altered in cancer cells.
Fumarate hydratase (FH) is part of the tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle, with mutations leading to fumarate accumulation and oncogenesis.
Succinate dehydrogenase complex, subunit B (SDHB) plays a role in both the TCA cycle and electron transport chain, with mutations linked to tumorigenesis.
APOL1 is involved in lysosomal membrane permeabilization, which can affect the replication and survival of Trypanosoma cruzi, the causative agent of Chagas disease.
TNF is a pro-inflammatory cytokine that mediates immune responses against Trypanosoma cruzi infection.
IFNG encodes interferon gamma, which activates macrophages and promotes an immune response crucial for controlling Trypanosoma cruzi infection.
IL6 is a cytokine involved in inflammatory responses and is upregulated during Trypanosoma cruzi infection.
IL10 is an anti-inflammatory cytokine that modulates the immune response to prevent tissue damage during Trypanosoma cruzi infection.
PTGS2, also known as COX-2, is upregulated in response to Trypanosoma cruzi infection and plays a role in the inflammatory process.
TCR (T-cell receptor) genes are involved in recognizing Trypanosoma cruzi antigens and initiating an adaptive immune response.
MMP9 is involved in tissue remodeling and may contribute to the cardiac pathology observed in chronic Chagas disease.
TLR2 is a Toll-like receptor that recognizes Trypanosoma cruzi components and triggers innate immune responses.
NOS2 encodes inducible nitric oxide synthase, which produces nitric oxide to control Trypanosoma cruzi infection in macrophages.
BCL2 anti-apoptotic gene modulates cell survival during Trypanosoma cruzi infection and can influence host cell apoptosis.
CXCL10 is a chemokine that recruits immune cells to the site of Trypanosoma cruzi infection, aiding in the control of the parasite.
CD8A is essential for the development and function of CD8+ T cells, which are crucial for killing Trypanosoma cruzi-infected cells.
Acts as a tumor suppressor and is frequently mutated in chemically induced cancers.
Involved in DNA repair and mutations can increase susceptibility to chemical carcinogens.
Plays a role in the repair of DNA damage from chemical carcinogens.
Mutations in this tumor suppressor gene are linked to chemical carcinogenesis in colorectal cancers.
Overexpression or mutation can be induced by certain chemicals, promoting carcinogenesis.
Mutations in this oncogene are a common event in chemically induced cancers.
Acts as an oncogene that can be overexpressed in response to chemical exposure, leading to cancer.
Encodes an enzyme involved in the metabolic activation of certain chemical carcinogens.
Involved in detoxifying carcinogens, and polymorphisms can increase cancer risk.
Roles in reducing quinones derived from chemical agents to less toxic forms.
Involved in nucleotide excision repair of DNA damage caused by chemical carcinogens.
A mismatch repair gene that corrects errors in DNA replication often induced by chemical carcinogens.
Involved in DNA mismatch repair and mutations can increase the risk of cancer development from carcinogens.
Pro-apoptotic gene that can be triggered in response to DNA damage from chemical carcinogens.
Tumor suppressor gene often inactivated in chemical carcinogenesis, preventing cell cycle arrest.
A key regulator of the cell cycle, mutation or inactivation promotes cancer progression due to chemical carcinogens.
Tumor suppressor gene that frequently mutates in response to chemical exposure, leading to uncontrolled cell growth.
Encodes an enzyme that metabolizes many low molecular weight carcinogens.
Its activation promotes cell survival and proliferation in response to chemical carcinogens.
CXCL1 encodes a chemokine involved in the chemotaxis of immune cells via CXCR2 receptor.
CXCR4 is a receptor that binds to the chemokine CXCL12 and mediates downstream signaling events.
CCR5 is a receptor for several chemokines including CCL3, CCL4, and CCL5, initiating signaling pathways.
CCL2 encodes a chemokine that recruits monocytes, memory T cells, and dendritic cells to sites of inflammation.
GNAI1 codes for a G protein involved in transducing signals from chemokine receptors to intracellular signaling pathways.
PLCB2 is involved in chemokine receptor signaling by generating second messengers.
PIK3CG encodes a catalytic subunit of PI3K, which is activated downstream of chemokine receptor signaling.
AKT1 is a serine/threonine kinase that is activated as part of the chemokine signaling pathway.
MAPK1 encodes a kinase activated in response to chemokines, involved in cell proliferation and migration.
NFATC1 is a transcription factor regulated by chemokine-induced calcium signaling.
RELA encodes a subunit of NF-κB that is activated in the chemokine signaling pathway affecting gene transcription.
GRK6 is involved in desensitizing chemokine receptors by phosphorylation.
RAC1 is a small GTPase activated by chemokine receptors, playing a role in cell motility.
ARAP3 is involved in the downstream signaling of chemokine receptors impacting migration and actin cytoskeleton remodeling.
Encodes the enzyme HMG-CoA reductase, which is the rate-limiting step in cholesterol biosynthesis.
Encodes the low-density lipoprotein receptor that mediates the uptake of cholesterol-rich LDL particles.
Encodes apolipoprotein E, which is involved in the transport and metabolism of cholesterol.
Encodes SREBP cleavage-activating protein, which regulates the activation of SREBP and cholesterol homeostasis.
Encodes sterol regulatory element-binding protein 2, a key transcription factor that controls cholesterol biosynthesis.
Encodes an enzyme involved in cholesterol metabolism and bile acid biosynthesis.
Encodes acetyl-CoA acetyltransferase 2, which is involved in cholesterol esterification.
Encodes ATP-binding cassette transporter A1, which is crucial for the efflux of cholesterol and phospholipids to apolipoproteins.
Encodes a protein involved in the intracellular trafficking of cholesterol.
Encodes sterol O-acyltransferase 1, which is involved in the conversion of free cholesterol into cholesteryl esters.
Encodes apolipoprotein B, a primary constituent of chylomicrons and LDL involved in lipid metabolism.
Encodes lysosomal acid lipase, which is important in the hydrolysis of cholesteryl esters within lysosomes.
Encodes microsomal triglyceride transfer protein, essential for the assembly and secretion of apolipoprotein B-containing lipoproteins.
Encodes sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1, which regulates genes of lipid biosynthesis, including cholesterol.
Encodes 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA synthase 1, a key enzyme in the mevalonate pathway of cholesterol synthesis.
Encodes insulin-induced gene 1, which regulates cholesterol synthesis by retaining SCAP/SREBP complex in the endoplasmic reticulum.
Encodes insulin-induced gene 2, which is involved in the retention of the SREBP/SCAP complex and regulation of cholesterol synthesis.
CHKA (Choline Kinase Alpha) catalyzes the phosphorylation of choline to phosphocholine, which is upregulated in many cancers.
CHKB (Choline Kinase Beta) also participates in the conversion of choline to phosphocholine, thereby influencing choline metabolism in cancer.
PCYT1A (Phosphate Cytidylyltransferase 1, Choline, Alpha) is involved in the synthesis of CDP-choline, a key step in phosphatidylcholine biosynthesis.
PCYT1B (Phosphate Cytidylyltransferase 1, Choline, Beta) plays a role in the synthesis of CDP-choline, impacting phosphatidylcholine production utilized by cancer cells.
CHPT1 (Choline Phosphotransferase 1) catalyzes the transfer of a phosphocholine group to diacylglycerol to form phosphatidylcholine, a crucial component in cancer cell membranes.
PLA2G4A (Phospholipase A2 Group IVA) is involved in the release of arachidonic acid from phosphatidylcholine, affecting lipid signaling in cancer cells.
PLA2G6 (Phospholipase A2 Group VI) hydrolyzes phosphatidylcholine, thereby modulating lipid metabolism and cellular signaling in cancer.
GPCPD1 (Glycerophosphocholine Phosphodiesterase 1) breaks down glycerophosphocholine, influencing choline availability in cancer cells.
GPCPD2 (Glycerophosphocholine Phosphodiesterase 2) hydrolyzes glycerophosphocholine, contributing to choline metabolism in cancer cells.
SLC44A1 (Solute Carrier Family 44 Member 1) is a choline transporter involved in the uptake of choline, essential for phosphatidylcholine synthesis in cancer.
SLC44A2 (Solute Carrier Family 44 Member 2) transports choline across membranes, impacting choline metabolism in cancer cells.
SLC44A3 (Solute Carrier Family 44 Member 3) facilitates the transport of choline, integral for choline metabolic pathways in cancer.
SLC44A4 (Solute Carrier Family 44 Member 4) contributes to choline transport, which is crucial for choline metabolism in cancer cells.
SLC5A7 (Solute Carrier Family 5 Member 7) is a high-affinity choline transporter implicated in the choline uptake necessary for phosphatidylcholine synthesis in cancer.
PTDSS1 (Phosphatidylserine Synthase 1) converts phosphatidylcholine to phosphatidylserine, impacting membrane lipid composition in cancer cells.
SEC23B (Sec23 Homolog B) is associated with vesicular trafficking of choline-containing compounds, influencing choline metabolism in cancer.
PLA2G2A (Phospholipase A2 Group IIA) hydrolyzes phosphatidylcholine to release free fatty acids and lysophosphatidylcholine, impacting inflammatory pathways in cancer.
ACAT1 (Acetyl-CoA Acetyltransferase 1) is involved in anabolic pathway regulation, influencing lipid metabolism including choline phospholipids in cancer.
SLC22A5 (Solute Carrier Family 22 Member 5) functions as a carnitine transporter, indirectly influencing choline metabolism through alterations in carnitine homeostasis.
CHAT encodes choline acetyltransferase, which is essential for synthesizing the neurotransmitter acetylcholine.
ACHE encodes acetylcholinesterase, the enzyme responsible for the breakdown of acetylcholine in the synaptic cleft.
CHT1 encodes the high-affinity choline transporter, which transports choline into the presynaptic neuron for acetylcholine synthesis.
SLC18A3 encodes the vesicular acetylcholine transporter, which loads acetylcholine into synaptic vesicles.
CHRNE encodes the epsilon subunit of the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor found in the neuromuscular junction.
CHRNB2 encodes the beta-2 subunit of the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor, which is crucial for receptor assembly and function.
GABBR1 encodes a subunit of the GABA-B receptor, which modulates acetylcholine release in the synapse.
GABBR2 encodes another subunit of the GABA-B receptor, playing a role in the modulation of cholinergic synapses.
SYP encodes synaptophysin, a protein involved in synaptic vesicle trafficking and release at synapses, including cholinergic synapses.
SNAP25 encodes a synaptosomal-associated protein essential for the synaptic vesicle fusion and neurotransmitter release.
The BCR gene forms a fusion gene with ABL1 as a result of the Philadelphia chromosome translocation, which is a hallmark of chronic myeloid leukemia.
ABL1 gene becomes constitutively active when fused with BCR, driving unchecked cell proliferation in chronic myeloid leukemia.
ABL2 shares structural and functional similarities with ABL1 and is thought to play a complementary role in certain cases of chronic myeloid leukemia.
CRKL is an adaptor protein that gets phosphorylated by BCR-ABL1, contributing to the signaling pathways that lead to leukemia.
GAB2 interacts with BCR-ABL1 and is involved in the enhancement of leukemic transformation.
LYN kinase is activated by BCR-ABL1 and mediates downstream signaling pathways involved in leukemogenesis.
HCK, a Src family kinase, is activated in BCR-ABL1 positive cells, contributing to the pathogenesis of chronic myeloid leukemia.
STAT5A is a transcription factor that is activated by BCR-ABL1, promoting the expression of genes important for cell proliferation and survival.
Like STAT5A, STAT5B is activated by BCR-ABL1 and plays a critical role in the expression of survival and proliferation genes in leukemia cells.
MYC is a target of BCR-ABL1 signaling and is involved in the regulation of genes that drive cell proliferation and growth in chronic myeloid leukemia.
It is a core component of the circadian oscillator that drives the expression of clock-controlled genes.
It forms a heterodimer with CLOCK and drives the transcription of circadian rhythm genes.
It is crucial for setting the timing of the circadian clock and in feedback regulation of CLOCK-BMAL1 activity.
It participates in the negative feedback loop that generates circadian rhythms.
It is involved in the negative feedback mechanism to regulate the circadian rhythms.
It represses CLOCK-BMAL1-mediated transcription in the circadian clock system.
It functions as an alternative partner to CLOCK in regulating circadian rhythms.
It phosphorylates PER proteins to regulate their stability and thus the tempo of the circadian clock.
It is involved in the maintenance and stabilization of the circadian clock.
It regulates expression of BMAL1, a key component of the circadian clock.
It represses the transcription of BMAL1, providing balance in the circadian machinery.
It is a transcription factor involved in driving the rhythmic expression of circadian genes.
It negatively regulates the transcription of clock genes and clock-controlled genes.
It phosphorylates and regulates the nuclear entry of circadian clock proteins.
It targets CRY proteins for ubiquitination and degradation, influencing circadian rhythm.
CLOCK is a core component of the circadian clock; it encodes a protein that regulates the expression of other circadian rhythm genes.
ARNTL (also known as BMAL1) forms a complex with CLOCK and is crucial for maintaining the circadian rhythm by activating transcription of target genes.
PER1 is a part of the PER protein family, which is essential for the feedback loop in the circadian clock mechanism.
PER2 is involved in the regulation of the circadian rhythm and interacts with other PER and CRY proteins in the feedback loop.
PER3 is another member of the PER protein family that contributes to the circadian clock's negative feedback loop.
CRY1 encodes a protein that plays an inhibitory role in the circadian clock by forming complexes with PER proteins and CLOCK:BMAL1.
CRY2 functions similarly to CRY1, involved in the regulation of circadian rhythms through its role in the feedback loop of gene expression.
NR1D1 (also known as REV-ERBα) represses BMAL1 expression and thereby influences the maintenance of circadian rhythms.
NR1D2 (also known as REV-ERBβ) plays a role similar to NR1D1, regulating the circadian rhythm by repressing BMAL1 expression.
DBP encodes a transcription factor involved in the regulation of genes that display circadian expression.
RORA encodes a nuclear receptor that regulates the expression of BMAL1, impacting the circadian rhythm.
CSNK1D (Casein Kinase 1 Delta) phosphorylates PER and CRY proteins, which is necessary for their degradation and the regulation of circadian rhythm.
CSNK1E (Casein Kinase 1 Epsilon) also phosphorylates PER and CRY proteins, similar to CSNK1D, and plays a role in the feedback loop of the circadian clock.
Encodes aconitase 1, which catalyzes the isomerization of citrate to isocitrate in the TCA cycle.
Encodes the alpha subunit of isocitrate dehydrogenase 3, which catalyzes the decarboxylation of isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate.
Encodes the beta subunit of isocitrate dehydrogenase 3, which is part of the enzyme complex converting isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate.
Encodes the gamma subunit of isocitrate dehydrogenase 3, involved in the oxidative decarboxylation of isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate.
Encodes the E1 component of the 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complex, which converts alpha-ketoglutarate to succinyl-CoA in the TCA cycle.
Encodes the E2 component of the 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complex involved in the TCA cycle.
Encodes the E3 component of both the pyruvate and 2-oxoglutarate dehydrogenase complexes, key enzymes in the TCA cycle.
Encodes the alpha subunit of succinate-CoA ligase, which converts succinyl-CoA to succinate.
Encodes the ADP-forming beta subunit of succinate-CoA ligase, converting succinyl-CoA to succinate in the TCA cycle.
Encodes the GTP-forming beta subunit of succinate-CoA ligase, involved in the conversion of succinyl-CoA to succinate.
Encodes the flavoprotein subunit of succinate dehydrogenase, which converts succinate to fumarate.
Encodes the iron-sulfur subunit of succinate dehydrogenase, essential for the conversion of succinate to fumarate.
Encodes the cytochrome b subunit of succinate dehydrogenase, which participates in the electron transport chain and TCA cycle.
Encodes the small subunit of succinate dehydrogenase, involved in the electron transport chain and TCA cycle.
Encodes fumarate hydratase, which catalyzes the reversible hydration of fumarate to malate.
Encodes cytosolic malate dehydrogenase, which catalyzes the conversion of malate to oxaloacetate.
Encodes mitochondrial malate dehydrogenase, which converts malate to oxaloacetate in the TCA cycle.
Encodes citrate synthase, which catalyzes the synthesis of citrate from oxaloacetate and acetyl-CoA.
The dopamine receptor D2 (DRD2) is linked to reinforcement and reward pathways implicated in cocaine addiction.
The dopamine transporter gene (SLC6A3) influences dopamine reuptake, affecting the reward pathways involved in cocaine addiction.
Brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) is involved in synaptic plasticity which is critical in the development of drug dependence and addiction.
Tyrosine hydroxylase (TH) is the rate-limiting enzyme in dopamine synthesis and plays a crucial role in dopamine-related reward pathways affected by cocaine use.
cAMP response element-binding protein (CREB1) is important for gene transcription related to neuronal changes observed in cocaine addiction.
The FOS gene is an immediate early gene that is rapidly induced by cocaine use, indicating neuronal activation involved in addiction processes.
Mu opioid receptor 1 (OPRM1) interacts with the endogenous opioid system, which modulates reward and the reinforcing effects of cocaine.
Glutamate receptor, ionotropic, N-methyl-D-aspartate 2B (GRIN2B), is involved in synaptic transmission and plasticity associated with cocaine addiction.
Catechol-O-methyltransferase (COMT) degrades catecholamines such as dopamine, influencing the dopaminergic system's role in cocaine addiction.
Period circadian regulator 1 (PER1) is implicated in circadian rhythm regulation and addiction behavior, including cocaine addiction.
Nuclear receptor subfamily 4 group A member 2 (NR4A2) has roles in dopaminergic neuron differentiation and function, relevant in cocaine's effect on the brain's reward system.
Encodes a component of the vacuolar ATPase that is crucial for proton transport in the collecting duct.
Encodes a subunit of the vacuolar ATPase involved in acid secretion in the intercalated cells of the collecting duct.
Encodes the anion exchanger 1, which is essential for bicarbonate transport in collecting ducts.
Encodes the anion exchanger 2, contributing to bicarbonate reabsorption and acid secretion in kidney.
Encodes the sodium/hydrogen exchanger 1, which plays a role in proton transport and pH regulation in the collecting duct.
Generic name for genes encoding the hydrogen ATPase pumps critical for acid secretion in the kidney.
Encodes carbonic anhydrase II, which is pivotal in the hydration of carbon dioxide and bicarbonate production in the collecting duct.
Encodes aquaporin-2, which indirectly affects acid secretion by regulating water reabsorption.
Gene family coding for vacuolar ATPase subunits that are directly involved in proton secretion in the collecting duct.
Mutations in the APC gene are a common initiating event in the development of colorectal cancer.
Mutations in KRAS are frequently found in colorectal cancer and are associated with tumor progression.
Mutations in TP53, which encodes the tumor suppressor protein p53, are frequently observed in colorectal cancer.
Loss of SMAD4 function is associated with increased tumorigenesis in colorectal cancer.
Mutations in the PIK3CA gene are involved in the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway, which is often dysregulated in colorectal cancer.
Mutations in BRAF, especially the V600E mutation, are prevalent in a subset of colorectal cancers.
Defects in the MLH1 gene lead to microsatellite instability, a hallmark of some colorectal cancers.
Mutations in MSH2 result in impaired DNA mismatch repair and increase the risk of colorectal cancer.
MSH6 mutations also contribute to the DNA mismatch repair deficiency observed in colorectal cancer.
Loss of the PTEN gene can lead to unregulated cell growth and survival, contributing to colorectal cancer development.
Mutations in AXIN2 can disrupt Wnt signaling, which is implicated in colorectal tumorigenesis.
Mutations in FBXW7, a gene involved in ubiquitin-mediated proteolysis, are observed in colorectal cancers.
Mutations in TGFBR2 impair TGF-β signaling, contributing to colorectal cancer progression.
E-cadherin, the protein encoded by CDH1, is involved in cell adhesion and its loss is associated with colorectal cancer metastasis.
Mutations in CTNNB1 lead to increased β-catenin activity, promoting colorectal cancer development.
RNF43 mutations interfere with Wnt signaling regulation, contributing to colorectal cancer.
Amplification or overexpression of ERBB2 can be observed in colorectal cancer, promoting cell proliferation and survival.
Alterations in NOTCH1 signaling can contribute to colorectal cancer cell differentiation and proliferation.
AKT1 activation, often due to PIK3CA mutations, leads to enhanced cell survival and growth in colorectal cancer.
Overexpression of CCND1 is involved in cell cycle dysregulation often seen in colorectal cancer.

Encodes Complement component 4A, an important protein in the classical complement pathway.
Encodes Plasminogen, crucial for clot dissolution in the coagulation cascade.
Encodes Coagulation Factor IX, essential for the intrinsic pathway of blood coagulation.
Encodes Complement component 2, a protein involved in the classical complement pathway.
Encodes Coagulation Factor X, which is activated to form a central enzyme in the coagulation process.
Encodes Tissue factor, which initiates the extrinsic pathway of blood coagulation.
Encodes alpha-1-antitrypsin, which inhibits various enzymes including those in the coagulation pathway.
Encodes Complement Factor H, a regulator of the alternative complement pathway.
Encodes Clusterin, involved in the regulation of complement activity.
Encodes Coagulation Factor VII, which participates in the extrinsic pathway of blood coagulation.
Encodes Antithrombin III, an inhibitor of thrombin in the coagulation cascade.
ACE2 is the receptor that SARS-CoV-2 uses to enter human cells.
TMPRSS2 facilitates viral entry by priming the spike protein of SARS-CoV-2.
DPP4 is a co-receptor that can enhance SARS-CoV-2 entry into cells.
FURIN is a protease that activates the spike protein of SARS-CoV-2, aiding in cell entry.
IFNAR1 is part of the interferon receptor complex that is crucial for the immune response to viral infections including SARS-CoV-2.
IL6 is a cytokine that is often elevated in severe cases of COVID-19 and contributes to the inflammatory response.
TLR3 recognizes viral RNA and initiates the antiviral immune response.
DDX58, also known as RIG-I, is involved in recognizing viral RNA and triggering an immune response.
TNF is a cytokine involved in systemic inflammation and its levels are elevated during severe COVID-19.
CXCL10 is a chemokine that recruits immune cells to sites of infection, and its expression is increased in COVID-19 patients.
CCL2 recruits monocytes to infection sites and is upregulated in COVID-19-related inflammation.
ISG15 is an interferon-stimulated gene that enhances the antiviral response.
STAT1 is involved in the signaling pathway triggered by interferons and is essential for antiviral defense.
MX1 is a GTPase induced by interferons that has antiviral activity against a range of viruses, including SARS-CoV-2.
CD147 may act as an alternative entry receptor for SARS-CoV-2.
JAK2 is involved in cytokine receptor signaling and its dysregulation can contribute to the cytokine storm in severe COVID-19.

Encodes an enzyme involved in the production of intermediate precursors for cortisol synthesis.
Encodes an enzyme that converts progesterone to deoxycorticosterone, a necessary step in cortisol biosynthesis.
Encodes an enzyme that converts deoxycortisol to cortisol in the adrenal cortex.
Encodes the Steroidogenic Acute Regulatory protein that facilitates cholesterol transport into mitochondria, where steroidogenesis begins.

Encodes a transcription factor essential for steroidogenic gene expression in adrenal glands.
Encodes an enzyme involved in cellular NADP synthesis, which is necessary for the proper function of several enzymes in cortisol biosynthesis.
Encodes an isozyme of HSD3B2 that is involved in steroid hormone biosynthesis, including cortisol.
Encodes Proopiomelanocortin, a precursor to ACTH, which stimulates cortisol production.
Encodes the glucocorticoid receptor which mediates the effects of cortisol in Cushing syndrome.
Mutations lead to McCune-Albright syndrome, a cause of Cushing syndrome due to autonomous adrenal hyperfunction.
Mutations are linked to Carney complex, an inherited condition that can cause Cushing syndrome.
Mutations in USP8 lead to pituitary adenomas secreting excess ACTH, causing Cushing disease.
Mutations can lead to MEN1-like syndrome, associated with adrenal tumors that cause Cushing syndrome.
Mutations are associated with Li-Fraumeni syndrome which can include adrenal tumors causing Cushing syndrome.
Mutations are associated with multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1, which can involve ACTH-secreting pituitary tumors causing Cushing syndrome.
Encodes proopiomelanocortin, precursor to ACTH which is involved in overproduction in Cushing syndrome.
Encodes a receptor for vasopressin which can play a role in ACTH regulation in Cushing syndrome.
Encodes the melanocortin 2 receptor (ACTH receptor) which is crucial in adrenal cortisol production linked to Cushing syndrome.
CBS encodes cystathionine beta-synthase, a key enzyme in the transsulfuration pathway, converting homocysteine to cystathionine.
CTH encodes cystathionine gamma-lyase, which converts cystathionine into cysteine, alpha-ketobutyrate, and ammonia.
MAT1A encodes methionine adenosyltransferase, crucial for the conversion of methionine into S-adenosylmethionine.
MTR encodes methionine synthase, which is responsible for the regeneration of methionine from homocysteine.

MTHFR encodes methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase, which is involved in the conversion of 5,10-methylenetetrahydrofolate to 5-methyltetrahydrofolate, a cofactor for homocysteine remethylation to methionine.
AHCY encodes adenosylhomocysteinase, which hydrolyzes S-adenosylhomocysteine to homocysteine and adenosine.
GNMT encodes glycine N-methyltransferase, which is involved in the regulation of S-adenosylmethionine levels.
BHMT encodes betaine-homocysteine methyltransferase, which catalyzes the methylation of homocysteine to form methionine using betaine as a methyl donor.
GCLC encodes the catalytic subunit of glutamate-cysteine ligase, which catalyzes the first step of glutathione biosynthesis from cysteine.
GCLM encodes the modifier subunit of glutamate-cysteine ligase, which assists in regulating the activity of the enzyme responsible for glutathione biosynthesis.
GPT2 encodes glutamic-pyruvic transaminase 2, which is involved in the aminotransferase reactions linked to amino acid metabolism including that of cysteine and methionine.
SARS encodes seryl-tRNA synthetase, involved in charging tRNA for protein synthesis and contributing indirectly to methionine metabolism.
MARS encodes methionyl-tRNA synthetase, which is essential for the ligation of methionine to tRNA(Met) for translation.

Encodes a cytokine that functions in inflammation and the maturation of B cells.
Encodes a proinflammatory cytokine that binds to TNF receptors mediating immune responses.
Encodes interferon-gamma, a cytokine critical for innate and adaptive immunity.
Encodes granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor involved in leukocyte differentiation.
Encodes a cytokine crucial for the growth, proliferation, and differentiation of T cells.
Encodes a cytokine that is important for lymphocyte cell survival and proliferation.
Encodes a receptor for multiple cytokines, including chemokines.
Encodes a receptor that binds to CXCL12 and plays a role in hematopoiesis.
Encodes a receptor for the transforming growth factor-beta involved in cellular processes including immune regulation.
Encodes the interleukin-1 receptor type I that binds IL1A and IL1B.
Encodes the interleukin-6 receptor which is involved in the regulation of immune responses.
Encodes a receptor for tumor necrosis factor-alpha involved in apoptosis and inflammation.
Encodes a receptor for type I interferons involved in antiviral responses.
Encodes cyclic GMP-AMP synthase, which recognizes cytosolic DNA and catalyzes the production of cGAMP.
Encodes STING (stimulator of interferon genes), which is activated by cGAMP produced by CGAS and initiates downstream signaling.
Encodes interferon gamma-inducible protein 16, which binds cytosolic DNA and activates STING.
Encodes DEAD-box helicase 41, a cytosolic DNA sensor that activates the STING pathway.
Encodes the catalytic subunit of RNA polymerase III, which can detect cytosolic DNA and produce non-coding RNA to trigger RIG-I signaling.
Encodes TANK-binding kinase 1, which is activated downstream of STING and phosphorylates IRF3 to induce type I interferons.
Encodes interferon regulatory factor 3, which is activated by TBK1 and induces transcription of type I interferon genes.
Encodes interferon regulatory factor 7, which is similarly activated in response to cytosolic DNA sensing and amplifies the interferon response.
Encodes an adapter protein that can be involved in downstream signaling of some cytosolic DNA sensors, indirectly linking to the pathway.
Encodes mitochondrial antiviral signaling protein, which can amplify downstream signaling in response to cytosolic RNA and indirectly link to cytosolic DNA pathways through crosstalk.
Encodes TIR domain-containing adapter molecule 1, which is involved in an alternative pathway for immune activation through cytosolic DNA sensing.

Encodes a helicase that can sense DNA and activate IRF3, playing a role in the cytosolic DNA-sensing pathway.
