A4GALT encodes α-1,4-galactosyltransferase, responsible for the synthesis of globosides, a subtype of glycosphingolipids.
GM2A encodes the GM2 ganglioside activator protein, which is essential for the degradation of GM2 gangliosides in lysosomes.
NEU3 encodes neuraminidase 3, which is involved in the catabolism of glycosphingolipids by removing sialic acid residues.
GBA encodes β-glucocerebrosidase, a lysosomal enzyme critical for the breakdown of glucosylceramide into glucose and ceramide.
Encodes an enzyme that participates in the second step of GPI-anchor biosynthesis.
Initiates GPI-anchor biosynthesis by transferring N-acetylglucosamine to phosphatidylinositol.
Involved in the transfer of mannose to the growing GPI anchor.
Part of the GPI-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase complex involved in the early steps of GPI-anchor biosynthesis.
Functions in the GPI-transamidase complex essential for GPI-anchor attachment to proteins.
A component of the GPI-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase complex, crucial for GPI-anchor biosynthesis.
Involved in the addition of mannose to the GPI precursor in the endoplasmic reticulum.
Catalyzes the addition of the third mannose in GPI-anchor assembly.
Encodes a glycosylphosphatidylinositol anchoring 1 protein, part of the GPI transamidase complex.
Encodes a subunit of the GPI transamidase complex crucial for attaching GPI-anchors to proteins.
Mediates the transfer of the second mannose in GPI biosynthesis.
A subunit of the GPI-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase complex, which is key for initiating GPI-anchor synthesis.
Involved in adding ethanolamine phosphate side branches to the GPI anchor.
Adds the second mannose during the elongation of the GPI-anchor.
Acts in the remodeling of GPI-anchors post-transfer to proteins.
Involved in the lipid remodeling of GPI-anchors after their attachment to proteins.
Plays a role in the lipid remodeling process of GPI-anchored proteins.
Encodes aconitase 2, an enzyme that catalyzes the isomerization of citrate to isocitrate in the TCA cycle, linking it to glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes isocitrate dehydrogenase 2, which converts isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate, linking the TCA cycle to glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes isocitrate dehydrogenase 3, another isoform crucial in the TCA cycle, influencing glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes mitochondrial malate dehydrogenase, which catalyzes the reversible oxidation of malate to oxaloacetate, involved in dicarboxylate metabolism.
Encodes cytosolic malate dehydrogenase, playing a key role in the malate-aspartate shuttle and indirectly linking to glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes fumarate hydratase, an enzyme in the TCA cycle that catalyzes the reversible hydration of fumarate to malate, connecting to glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes succinate dehydrogenase complex flavoprotein subunit A, an enzyme in the TCA cycle that also participates in dicarboxylate metabolism.
Encodes glutamate dehydrogenase 1, which deaminates glutamate to alpha-ketoglutarate, indirectly linking to glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes 4-hydroxy-2-oxoglutarate aldolase 1, involved in the hydroxyproline metabolism pathway, which interacts with glyoxylate.
Encodes alanine-glyoxylate aminotransferase, which converts glyoxylate and L-alanine to glycine and pyruvate, directly involved in glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes glycerate kinase, which converts glycerate to 3-phosphoglycerate, participating in glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes homogentisate 1,2-dioxygenase, which metabolizes homogentisate to maleylacetoacetate, thus linking to dicarboxylate metabolism.
Encodes oxoglutarate dehydrogenase, an enzyme in the TCA cycle that converts alpha-ketoglutarate to succinyl-CoA, linking it to glyoxylate metabolism.
Encodes the precursor protein for gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH).
Encodes kisspeptin, which acts on GPR54 to stimulate the release of GnRH.
Encodes a receptor (GPR54) that mediates the stimulatory effect of kisspeptin on GnRH neurons.
Produces nitric oxide that modulates GnRH secretion.
Encodes neurokinin B, which stimulates GnRH release.
Encodes the receptor for neurokinin B, which regulates GnRH secretion.
Encodes the GnRH receptor that mediates the effects of GnRH on target cells.
Encodes estrogen receptor alpha which influences the regulation of GnRH neurons.
Produces prokineticin 2, which has roles in the regulation of GnRH neuron migration and secretion.
A receptor named for its role in mediating kisspeptin signaling affecting the release of GnRH.
Influences the development and function of GnRH neurons.
Essential for the development and maintenance of GnRH neurons.
Encodes calmodulin, which is involved in Ca2+ signaling pathways that play a role in GnRH release.
Encodes the receptor necessary for kisspeptin signaling to stimulate GnRH secretion.
Encodes the gonadotropin-releasing hormone which is the primary ligand in the GnRH signaling pathway.
Encodes the GnRH receptor which binds to GnRH and initiates the signaling cascade.
Encodes a G-protein subunit involved in activating phospholipase C in the GnRH signaling pathway.
Encodes a G-protein subunit that mediates the signaling downstream of the GnRH receptor.
Encodes phospholipase C beta 1 which plays a role in the hydrolysis of PIP2 to produce IP3 and DAG.
Encodes phospholipase C beta 4, another isoform involved in the production of second messengers in the GnRH signaling pathway.
Encodes protein kinase C alpha which is activated by DAG produced in the GnRH signaling pathway and involved in downstream signaling.
Encodes a protein that binds and regulates protein kinase C which is involved in the signaling pathway of GnRH.
Encodes ERK1, a kinase activated downstream in the GnRH signaling pathway involved in cell proliferation and differentiation.
Encodes ERK2, a kinase activated downstream in the GnRH signaling pathway important for various cellular responses.
Encodes a subunit of Ca2+/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase involved in the calcium signaling part of the GnRH pathway.
Encodes another subunit of Ca2+/calmodulin-dependent protein kinase II which plays a role in GnRH-induced gene expression.
Human leukocyte antigen class II genes are directly involved in antigen presentation, which is critical in the immune response during graft-versus-host disease.
Tumor necrosis factor is a cytokine involved in systemic inflammation and is a key mediator in graft-versus-host disease.
Interleukin-2 is a cytokine that regulates white blood cells and is implicated in the activation and proliferation of T cells in graft-versus-host disease.
FOXP3 is essential for the regulatory function of Tregs, which are critical in maintaining immune tolerance during graft-versus-host disease.
Interferon gamma is a cytokine produced by T cells and natural killer cells, playing a pivotal role in promoting inflammation in graft-versus-host disease.
Interleukin-10 is an anti-inflammatory cytokine involved in immune regulation and suppression of graft-versus-host disease.
CCR5 is a chemokine receptor involved in the migration of immune cells to sites of inflammation, including tissues affected in graft-versus-host disease.
CTLA4 is an immune checkpoint that helps regulate T-cell activation and is involved in mitigating the immune response in graft-versus-host disease.
Colony stimulating factor 2 (GM-CSF) is a cytokine that stimulates granulocyte and macrophage function, contributing to the inflammatory response in graft-versus-host disease.
Interleukin-6 is a cytokine involved in inflammation and the acute phase response, playing a role in the pathogenesis of graft-versus-host disease.
STAT3 is a transcription factor activated by cytokines like IL-6 and IL-10, playing a central role in immune responses during graft-versus-host disease.
Chemokine receptor CXCR3 is involved in T cell trafficking to inflammatory sites, including those affected by graft-versus-host disease.
NOD2 is involved in the recognition of bacterial molecules and the regulation of immune responses, contributing to intestinal inflammation in graft-versus-host disease.
GH1 encodes the growth hormone, which is directly responsible for promoting growth and development.
GHRH encodes growth hormone-releasing hormone, which stimulates the production and release of growth hormone.
GHRHR encodes the receptor for growth hormone-releasing hormone, which mediates its action on growth hormone synthesis.
GHR encodes the growth hormone receptor, which is essential for growth hormone action in target tissues.
IGF1 encodes insulin-like growth factor 1, which mediates many of the growth-promoting effects of growth hormone.
IGF1R encodes the receptor for insulin-like growth factor 1, which is crucial for IGF1 signal transduction.
STAT5B encodes a transcription factor activated by the growth hormone receptor to mediate growth hormone effects.
JAK2 encodes a tyrosine kinase that is activated by the growth hormone receptor and plays a key role in signal transduction.
POMC encodes a precursor protein that can be cleaved to form ACTH, which can indirectly influence growth hormone levels through cortisol regulation.
SST encodes somatostatin, which inhibits the release of growth hormone.
SSTR2 encodes one of the receptors for somatostatin, mediating its inhibitory effects on growth hormone release.
PIT1 (POU1F1) encodes a pituitary-specific transcription factor crucial for the development and function of growth hormone-producing cells.
PROP1 encodes a transcription factor necessary for pituitary development and function, influencing growth hormone production.
HESX1 encodes a homeobox gene involved in pituitary gland development and can affect growth hormone synthesis and secretion.
GHRHR encodes the growth hormone-releasing hormone receptor, which is necessary for GHRH to stimulate GH synthesis.
GH2 encodes a variant form of growth hormone that contributes to overall growth regulation, particularly during pregnancy.
Encodes the alpha subunit of Hypoxia-Inducible Factor 1, which is a central regulator of the cellular response to low oxygen levels.
Encodes the aryl hydrocarbon receptor nuclear translocator, which dimerizes with HIF1A to form the functional HIF-1 complex.
Encodes prolyl hydroxylase domain-containing enzyme 2 (PHD2), which hydroxylates HIF1A under normoxic conditions, leading to its degradation.
Encodes the von Hippel-Lindau protein that targets hydroxylated HIF1A for ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation.
Encodes HIF-2 alpha, which is similar in function to HIF1A and activates transcription of genes involved in the response to hypoxia.
Encodes pyruvate dehydrogenase kinase 1, which is upregulated by HIF-1 and involved in metabolic reprogramming under hypoxic conditions.
Encodes lactate dehydrogenase A, which is upregulated by HIF-1 to aid in anaerobic glycolysis.
Encodes vascular endothelial growth factor A, an angiogenic factor upregulated by HIF-1 to promote blood vessel formation.
Encodes GLUT1, a glucose transporter upregulated by HIF-1 to increase glucose uptake under hypoxic conditions.
Encodes adrenomedullin, a vasodilatory peptide whose expression is upregulated by HIF-1 to facilitate cellular adaptation to hypoxia.
Encodes BCL2/adenovirus E1B 19kDa protein-interacting protein 3, which is involved in hypoxia-induced apoptosis and is regulated by HIF-1.
Encodes inducible nitric oxide synthase, which is upregulated by HIF-1 and contributes to the production of nitric oxide in response to hypoxia.
Encodes prolyl 4-hydroxylase subunit alpha 1, which is involved in collagen synthesis and is regulated by HIF-1 during the adaptive response to hypoxia.
Encodes phosphoglycerate kinase 1, which is involved in glycolysis and is upregulated by HIF-1 to enhance ATP production under hypoxic conditions.
Encodes matrix metallopeptidase 2, which is regulated by HIF-1 and involved in extracellular matrix remodeling during angiogenesis.
SHH encodes Sonic Hedgehog, the primary ligand involved in Hedgehog signaling.
PTCH1 encodes the Patched 1 receptor which binds to Hedgehog ligands and normally inhibits pathway activation.
SMO encodes Smoothened, a G-protein-coupled receptor that activates downstream signaling when Hedgehog ligands bind to Patched receptors.
GLI1 is a transcription factor that acts as an effector of Hedgehog signaling by mediating the transcription of target genes.
GLI2 is a transcription factor that acts as both a mediator and regulator of Hedgehog signaling.
GLI3 is a transcription factor that can act as a repressor or activator in the Hedgehog signaling pathway depending on its processing state.
SUFU encodes Suppressor of Fused, which negatively regulates the Hedgehog signaling pathway by binding to GLI transcription factors.
PTCH2 encodes Patched 2, a receptor similar to PTCH1 that also binds Hedgehog ligands and regulates pathway activation.
HHIP encodes Hedgehog Interacting Protein, a regulatory protein that inhibits Hedgehog signaling by binding to Hedgehog ligands.
IFRD1 is involved in the regulation of gene expression influenced by the Hedgehog pathway.
BTRC encodes Beta-Transducin Repeat Containing E3 Ubiquitin Protein Ligase, which targets GLI proteins for ubiquitination and degradation.
CDON encodes a cell adhesion molecule that is a coreceptor for Hedgehog ligands.
BOC encodes a cell surface receptor that acts as a coreceptor, enhancing Hedgehog signaling.
GAS1 encodes a protein that facilitates Hedgehog signaling by modulating the interaction between Hedgehog ligands and their receptors.
KIF7 encodes a kinesin family member that regulates the spatial and temporal activity of GLI transcription factors in the Hedgehog pathway.
PRKX encodes Protein Kinase X-linked, a protein kinases potentially involved in modulating Hedgehog pathway via phosphorylation of pathway components.
GATA1 is a transcription factor essential for the development of erythroid and megakaryocytic lineages in hematopoiesis.
RUNX1 is crucial for the regulation of hematopoietic stem cell emergence and differentiation towards various blood cell types.
TAL1 is essential for early hematopoietic progenitor cell development and differentiation into erythroid and megakaryocytic lineages.
CEBPA is a transcription factor necessary for the differentiation of myeloid progenitors into granulocytes and monocytes.
MYB is a key regulator of hematopoietic stem cell proliferation and differentiation.
SPI1 (PU.1) is a transcription factor critical for the differentiation of myeloid and lymphoid progenitors.
IKZF1 (Ikaros) is important for the development and function of lymphoid lineages, particularly in T and B cell differentiation.
LMO2 aids in the regulation of hematopoietic stem cell development and differentiation into various blood cell types.
FLI1 is involved in the differentiation of megakaryocytes and the maturation of erythroid cells.
CSF3R encodes the receptor for granulocyte-colony stimulating factor, essential for the proliferation and differentiation of granulocyte precursors.
IL7R encodes the receptor for interleukin-7, critical for the survival and differentiation of T and B cell progenitors.
EPO (erythropoietin) is a hormone that regulates erythroid progenitor cell survival, proliferation, and differentiation into red blood cells.
KIT encodes the receptor c-Kit which is involved in the survival, proliferation, and differentiation of hematopoietic stem cells and progenitors.
NOTCH1 signaling is essential for T cell lineage specification and development within the thymus.
TP53 plays a role in the regulation of hematopoietic stem cell quiescence, self-renewal, and differentiation to prevent leukemogenesis.

The HBV gene encodes the components of the Hepatitis B virus, including surface antigens, core protein, and polymerase, which are integral to the virus's ability to infect liver cells and cause Hepatitis B.
CCL2 is involved in the recruitment of monocytes, memory T cells, and dendritic cells to the site of infection, which can influence the immune response against Hepatitis B virus.
CXCL10 is a chemokine that promotes the trafficking of immune cells to the liver, playing a role in the inflammatory response during Hepatitis B infection.
IFNG, which encodes interferon-gamma, is crucial for antiviral defense mechanisms and can help in controlling Hepatitis B virus replication.
TNF, or tumor necrosis factor, is a cytokine that mediates inflammation and can contribute to liver damage and immune response during Hepatitis B infection.
IL6 is a cytokine involved in inflammation and immune activation, playing a role in the pathogenesis and progression of Hepatitis B.
HLA-DRA is part of the major histocompatibility complex class II (MHC II) and is important for antigen presentation to T cells, which is crucial for immune response against Hepatitis B.
CD8A encodes the CD8 alpha chain of cytotoxic T cells, which are essential for killing Hepatitis B virus-infected cells.
The PGC gene encodes pepsinogen C, which although primarily involved in digestion, has been found to have altered expression in Hepatitis B-associated liver disease.
SLCO1B1 encodes a liver-specific organic anion transporter; its expression can be influenced by Hepatitis B, affecting drug transport and metabolism in the liver.
IL10 is an anti-inflammatory cytokine that can modulate immune responses and is known to influence the progression of Hepatitis B infection.
IFNL3, also known as IL28B, is involved in the antiviral response and genetic polymorphisms in this gene are associated with the spontaneous clearance of Hepatitis C virus.
OAS1 is a part of the interferon-induced antiviral response pathway and its polymorphisms have been linked to Hepatitis C virus persistence and treatment outcome.
IL10 encodes an anti-inflammatory cytokine which can influence the immune response in Hepatitis C infection, helping to balance inflammation and limit liver damage.
HLA-DQB1 is involved in the immune response and certain alleles have been associated with either an increased risk of chronic Hepatitis C or a higher likelihood of spontaneous viral clearance.
CD81 encodes a tetraspanin that serves as a coreceptor for Hepatitis C virus entry into host cells.
EIF2AK2, also known as PKR, mediates the antiviral effects of interferons by inhibiting protein synthesis and is thus crucial in the host response to Hepatitis C infection.
TLR3 is a gene coding for toll-like receptor 3, which recognizes viral double-stranded RNA and initiates an innate immune response against Hepatitis C.
MX1 is an interferon-inducible gene encoding dynamin-like GTPase, which has direct antiviral activity against Hepatitis C virus.
STAT1 is involved in the JAK-STAT signaling pathway, which is activated by interferons to induce an antiviral state in response to Hepatitis C infection.
RBM3 is a cold-inducible RNA binding protein that has been associated with elevated mRNA levels in Hepatitis C liver tissues and might play a role in the virus lifecycle's regulation.
CXCL10, also known as IP-10, is a chemokine induced by interferon that recruits immune cells to the site of Hepatitis C infection and plays a role in the inflammatory response.
IRF7 is a transcription factor that regulates the expression of type I interferon genes in response to Hepatitis C infection.
TP53 is frequently mutated in hepatocellular carcinoma, leading to loss of its tumor suppressor function.
CTNNB1 mutations result in aberrant activation of the Wnt signaling pathway, which promotes hepatocellular carcinoma development.
TERT promoter mutations lead to increased telomerase activity, contributing to hepatocellular carcinoma cell immortalization.
AXIN1 mutations disrupt the Wnt signaling pathway, promoting tumor growth in hepatocellular carcinoma.
RB1 gene inactivation leads to disrupted cell cycle control, which is associated with hepatocellular carcinoma.
ARID1A mutations impair chromatin remodeling, which is implicated in the pathogenesis of hepatocellular carcinoma.
CDKN2A gene deletions or mutations lead to loss of its tumor suppressor function, contributing to hepatocellular carcinoma.
PIK3CA mutations activate the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway, which is involved in hepatocellular carcinoma progression.
MET gene amplification or mutation leads to enhanced signaling for cell growth and survival in hepatocellular carcinoma.
MYC amplification is frequently observed in hepatocellular carcinoma, driving tumorigenesis and cancer cell proliferation.
VEGFA overexpression promotes angiogenesis, which is crucial for hepatocellular carcinoma growth and metastasis.
HNF1A mutations inhibit differentiation and support the proliferation of hepatocytes, contributing to hepatocellular carcinoma.
NFE2L2 mutations lead to constitutive activation of antioxidant response elements, aiding in hepatocellular carcinoma cell survival.
KEAP1 mutations result in dysregulation of the NFE2L2 pathway, promoting hepatocellular carcinoma development.
CCND1 (cyclin D1) overexpression accelerates cell cycle progression, which is often observed in hepatocellular carcinoma.
FGF19 overexpression leads to sustained activation of receptor tyrosine kinase signaling, contributing to hepatocellular carcinoma.
IFNA1 encodes an interferon alpha protein that plays a critical role in the innate immune response to Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
IFNB1 is important in antiviral defense by encoding interferon beta, which is involved in the response to Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
IFNG, encoding interferon gamma, is crucial for activating immune cells during Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
TNF is a pro-inflammatory cytokine involved in immune responses to Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
IL6 encodes interleukin 6, a cytokine that is part of the body's response to infection, including Herpes simplex virus 1.
IL10 encodes interleukin 10, which modulates inflammation and immune response during Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
CCL2 is a chemokine involved in recruiting immune cells to the site of Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
CXCL10 encodes a chemokine that attracts immune cells to areas infected by Herpes simplex virus 1.
STAT1 is involved in the signal transduction pathway for type I and II interferons, playing a key role in the response to Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
STAT2 is required for the activation of interferon-stimulated genes during Herpes simplex virus 1 infection.
TLR3 recognizes viral double-stranded RNA, including from Herpes simplex virus 1, triggering the antiviral response.
DDX58 encodes the RIG-I protein that senses viral RNA and mediates the immune response to Herpes simplex virus 1.
IFIH1 encodes a sensor of viral RNA, acting in the immune response against Herpes simplex virus 1.
MST1 is a core kinase in the Hippo signaling pathway that initiates the kinase cascade.
MST2 is closely related to MST1 and acts as a core component kinase within the Hippo signaling pathway.
Sav1 acts as an adaptor protein facilitating MST1/2 kinase activity in the Hippo signaling pathway.
LATS1 is a downstream kinase in the Hippo signaling pathway responsible for phosphorylating YAP1.
LATS2, like LATS1, phosphorylates YAP1 and TAZ, serving as a crucial downstream kinase in the Hippo pathway.
YAP1 is a transcription co-activator that is inhibited by phosphorylation through the Hippo pathway, regulating growth and apoptosis.
TAZ, similar to YAP1, is a transcription co-activator inhibited by Hippo pathway-mediated phosphorylation, influencing cell proliferation and differentiation.
WW45 acts as a cofactor in the Hippo signaling pathway aiding MST1/2 activation.
NF2 (Merlin) acts as a regulator of the Hippo pathway linking cellular structure to signal transduction.
AMOT family members are involved in the regulation of YAP1/TAZ through the Hippo pathway.
TEAD1 is a transcription factor that forms complexes with YAP1/TAZ to mediate gene expression downstream of the Hippo pathway.
TEAD2 acts similarly to TEAD1, forming complexes with YAP1/TAZ to control transcription of target genes.
TEAD3 partners with YAP1/TAZ to drive Hippo pathway-regulated gene expression.
TEAD4, like other TEAD family members, binds YAP1/TAZ to execute gene transcription in the Hippo pathway.
HAL encodes histidine ammonia-lyase, which is directly involved in the first step of histidine catabolism.
GLUD1 encodes glutamate dehydrogenase 1, which converts the product of histidine catabolism to alpha-ketoglutarate in the TCA cycle.
GLUD2 encodes a mitochondrial glutamate dehydrogenase, which also contributes to the conversion of glutamate formed during histidine metabolism.
PAH encodes phenylalanine hydroxylase whose activity influences histidine levels indirectly by impacting amino acid metabolism balance.
HDC encodes histidine decarboxylase which catalyzes the conversion of histidine to histamine.
GSTM1 encodes glutathione S-transferase mu 1, which helps in detoxification reactions involved in the broader process of amino acid metabolism, including histidine.
UPB1 encodes ureidopropionase beta, which catalyzes the last step of the pyrimidine degradation pathway, intersecting amino acid catabolism pathways including those of histidine.
OTC encodes ornithine carbamoyltransferase, playing a role in the urea cycle which is important for the disposal of nitrogen derived from amino acid metabolism including histidine.
BRCA1 is involved in the repair of DNA double-strand breaks through homologous recombination.
BRCA2 facilitates the loading of RAD51 onto single-stranded DNA during homologous recombination.
RAD51 mediates the strand invasion step of homologous recombination by forming filaments on single-stranded DNA.
RAD52 assists in the annealing of complementary single-stranded DNA during homologous recombination.
RAD54 interacts with RAD51 to enhance its strand invasion activity during homologous recombination.
MRE11 is part of the MRN complex which is crucial for the initial processing of double-strand breaks in homologous recombination.
RAD50, as part of the MRN complex, plays a key role in tethering DNA ends and facilitating their processing during homologous recombination.
NBN (Nibrin) is a component of the MRN complex involved in the detection and signaling of double-strand breaks during homologous recombination.
DMC1 is a meiosis-specific homolog of RAD51 that catalyzes strand exchange during homologous recombination.
BLM is a helicase that helps resolve Holliday junctions, a key intermediate in homologous recombination.
EXO1 is an exonuclease that processes DNA ends to generate single-stranded DNA necessary for homologous recombination.
TOP3A works with BLM to resolve DNA entanglements and double Holliday junctions during the homologous recombination process.
RPA1 binds single-stranded DNA and protects it during the homologous recombination process.
SPO11 introduces double-strand breaks to initiate homologous recombination during meiosis.
PALB2 interacts with BRCA2 to stabilize the RAD51 nucleoprotein filament during DNA repair by homologous recombination.
FANCD2 is part of the Fanconi anemia pathway, which intersects with homologous recombination for the repair of interstrand crosslinks.
FANCI works with FANCD2 in the Fanconi anemia pathway to coordinate the repair of DNA damage through homologous recombination.
RAD51C forms a complex with other RAD51 paralogs to promote the homologous recombination process.
RAD51B, as part of the RAD51 paralog complex, functions in the stabilization of RAD51 filaments during homologous recombination.
XRCC2 is a RAD51 paralog that helps maintain the stability and efficiency of RAD51-mediated strand exchange in homologous recombination.
XRCC3 is another RAD51 paralog that assists in the repair of DNA double-strand breaks by homologous recombination.
RECQL5 suppresses inappropriate recombination events preventing genome instability during homologous recombination.
TAX is a viral oncogene of HTLV-1 that plays a critical role in the transformation of infected T-cells.
HBZ is a viral gene of HTLV-1 that regulates viral latency and promotes the proliferation of infected cells.
NFAT5 is involved in the transcriptional response to HTLV-1 through interactions with viral proteins.
CREB is activated by HTLV-1 TAX protein and contributes to the transcriptional activation of viral and cellular genes.
IL2 is upregulated in HTLV-1-infected cells, promoting T-cell proliferation and survival.
CD4 is the primary receptor on T-cells for HTLV-1 entry into the host cells.
CCR4 is a chemokine receptor upregulated in HTLV-1-infected T-cells enhancing their migratory capacity.
CCL22 is a chemokine ligand whose expression is increased in HTLV-1-infected cells attracting CCR4+ T-cells.
FOXP3 expression can be induced by HTLV-1, contributing to immune evasion and regulatory T-cell expansion.
IKBKB is involved in the activation of NF-kB pathway which is frequently activated in HTLV-1 infection.
TP53 function is often disrupted by HTLV-1 TAX protein leading to uncontrolled cell growth and survival.
BCL2 is upregulated by HTLV-1 to inhibit apoptosis and promote cell survival.
IRF3 activation is critical for the induction of antiviral responses during HCMV infection.
IFNAR1 mediates the type I interferon response that inhibits HCMV replication.
STAT1 is activated by IFN signaling during HCMV infection, leading to the expression of antiviral genes.
MX1 is an interferon-inducible gene that inhibits HCMV replication.
TLR2 recognizes HCMV components, triggering an innate immune response.
TNF is a pro-inflammatory cytokine activated during HCMV infection, contributing to antiviral defense.
CD8A encodes a protein essential for the function of cytotoxic T cells, which target HCMV-infected cells.
IL6 is produced during HCMV infection and modulates the immune response.
IFNB1 encodes interferon-beta, crucial for antiviral defense against HCMV.
ICAM1 is upregulated during HCMV infection and plays a role in leukocyte adhesion and immune response.
CCL5 enhances the recruitment of immune cells to sites of HCMV infection.
UL144 is an HCMV gene that modulates host immune responses to facilitate viral persistence.
pp65 is an HCMV protein that interferes with host immune responses to aid in viral evasion.
IFI16 senses HCMV DNA and activates innate immune signaling pathways.
IL10 is an immunoregulatory cytokine that can be induced by HCMV to suppress host immune responses.
CD4 is the primary receptor on T cells that HIV-1 binds to for entry into the host cell.
CCR5 acts as a co-receptor that HIV-1 uses along with CD4 to gain entry into macrophages and T cells.
CXCR4 is another co-receptor utilized by HIV-1 to infect T cells, particularly in later stages of infection.
TRIM5 is involved in the intracellular defense against viral infections including HIV by recognizing and targeting the viral capsid for degradation.
APOBEC3G is a host enzyme that introduces mutations into the viral DNA, disrupting the infection process of HIV-1.
SAMHD1 restricts HIV-1 replication in dendritic cells and macrophages by degrading intracellular dNTPs.
BST2, also known as tetherin, impedes the release of new viral particles from infected cells.
IFITM3 restricts HIV-1 entry by interfering with viral fusion to the host cell membrane.
LEDGF acts as a tethering factor that facilitates integration of HIV-1 DNA into the host genome.
CCR2 is a co-receptor that can influence the efficiency of HIV-1 entry into macrophages.
IL7R signaling affects T cell survival, indirectly impacting HIV-1 reservoir dynamics.
TNF is a cytokine that influences the immune response and inflammation during HIV-1 infection.
IL6 is a pro-inflammatory cytokine that is often elevated during HIV-1 infection and can affect disease progression.
STAT1 is involved in the signaling cascade of interferons, which are part of the immune response against HIV-1.
SPI1, also known as PU.1, is a transcription factor that regulates genes involved in immune responses to HIV-1.
NFKB1 is a transcription factor that regulates the expression of various genes involved in the immune response to HIV-1.
HPV E6 protein targets TP53 for degradation, disrupting cell cycle control.
HPV E7 protein binds and inactivates the retinoblastoma protein, encoded by RB1, promoting unchecked cell division.
HPV E7-mediated degradation of RB1 leads to upregulation of CDKN2A, which encodes p16INK4a, a marker for HPV-associated cancers.
HPV infection can activate TERT, which encodes the telomerase reverse transcriptase, promoting cellular immortality.
HPV E6 and E7 oncoproteins can lead to the overexpression of MYC, promoting cell proliferation.
HPV E7 disrupts the RB1-E2F1 complex, releasing E2F1 to activate genes that drive cell cycle progression.
HPV E7 increases CCNE1 (Cyclin E1) levels, aiding in the transition from G1 to S phase of the cell cycle.
HPV E7 activates CDK2 (cyclin-dependent kinase 2) which is crucial for cell cycle progression.
HPV E7 facilitates the overexpression of MCM7, a gene involved in DNA replication initiation.
HPV infection can interfere with ATM, leading to impaired DNA damage response.
HPV infection can affect the function of BRCA1, which is crucial for DNA repair.
HPV infection causes disruption in FANCD2, impacting the DNA repair pathway.
HPV can upregulate EGFR, leading to increased cell proliferation signals.
HPV infection can increase PD-L1 expression, helping the virus evade immune detection.
HPV infection can result in the activation of PIK3CA, promoting cell survival and growth.
HPV E6 and E7 oncoproteins can activate AKT1 signaling pathways, contributing to cell survival and growth.
HPV can lead to PTEN inactivation, which results in uncontrolled cell growth and survival.
HPV E6 targets HSPA5 (BiP/GRP78) to inhibit apoptosis.
HPV can suppress the expression of IFNB1, hindering the antiviral immune response.
HPV infection can lead to increased IL6 expression, fostering a pro-inflammatory environment.
HPV can increase IL10 expression, which suppresses immune responses.
Mutations in the HTT gene cause Huntington disease by producing an abnormal form of the huntingtin protein that leads to neurodegeneration.
Reduced levels of BDNF have been observed in the brains of Huntington disease patients due to impaired transcriptional regulation by mutant huntingtin.
HAP1 interacts with huntingtin protein and is implicated in intracellular trafficking, which is disrupted in Huntington disease.
The downregulation of PPARGC1A by mutant huntingtin affects mitochondrial biogenesis and function, contributing to neurodegeneration.
REST is sequestered by mutant huntingtin outside the nucleus, leading to dysregulation of neuronal survival genes in Huntington disease.
Altered CREB1 function due to disrupted CREB signaling pathways contributes to neuronal dysfunction seen in Huntington disease.
ATXN1 is involved in protein aggregation processes, which are a hallmark of neurodegenerative diseases including Huntington disease.
CLU is associated with the clearance of misfolded proteins, a process that is impaired in Huntington disease.
PINK1 mutations affect mitochondrial quality control, and mitochondrial dysfunction is a feature of Huntington disease pathology.
UBE3A encodes an E3 ubiquitin ligase, and dysfunction in the ubiquitin-proteasome system is observed in Huntington disease.
Mutations in MYH7 are a common cause of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy as it encodes the beta-myosin heavy chain important for cardiac muscle contraction.
MYBPC3 encodes the cardiac myosin-binding protein C, and its mutations lead to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
TNNT2 encodes the cardiac troponin T protein, which is crucial for muscle contraction regulation, and mutations are associated with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
TPM1 encodes alpha-tropomyosin, which plays a role in muscle contraction, and mutations in TPM1 are linked to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
TNNI3 encodes cardiac troponin I, an inhibitory protein, and its mutations often result in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
MYL2 encodes the regulatory myosin light chain 2, and mutations contribute to the development of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
MYL3 encodes myosin light chain 3, another regulatory protein, with mutations associated with hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
ACTC1 encodes cardiac actin, an essential component of the sarcomere, and mutations are linked to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
CSRP3 encodes muscle LIM protein, a part of the cardiac muscle cell structure, and mutations can cause hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.

A serine/threonine-protein kinase involved in MAPK signaling pathway, mutations are common in melanoma.
Encodes a protein that helps regulate cell growth and adhesion, mutations are linked to colorectal cancer.
Encodes beta-catenin, part of the WNT signaling pathway, mutations can lead to cancer.
Involved in TGF-beta signaling, plays a role in cancer suppression.
Regulatory subunit of PI3K, involved in cell growth, proliferation, differentiation, and survival.
Encodes a receptor involved in cell differentiation, aberrant signaling is linked to cancer.
Encodes anaplastic lymphoma kinase, mutations are implicated in several cancer types including non-small cell lung cancer.
Involved in the production of beta-amyloid plaques, a hallmark of Alzheimer's disease.
Mutations in this gene are linked to early-onset Alzheimer's disease by affecting amyloid precursor protein processing.
Encodes the tau protein, which forms neurofibrillary tangles in neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's and frontotemporal dementia.
Encodes alpha-synuclein, a major component of Lewy bodies found in Parkinson's disease.
Mutations in LRRK2 are the most common genetic cause of Parkinson's disease.
Mutations in this gene lead to mitochondrial dysfunction and are associated with early-onset Parkinson's disease.
Mutations in PARK2 (parkin) are associated with autosomal recessive juvenile Parkinsonism and affect protein degradation.
The gene responsible for producing huntingtin, whose aggregates cause neuronal cell death in Huntington's disease.
Mutations in this RNA-binding protein gene are linked to amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) and frontotemporal dementia.
Encodes TDP-43, which aggregates in ALS and frontotemporal lobar degeneration.
Mutations in GRN cause frontotemporal dementia by affecting progranulin levels, leading to neuroinflammation and cell death.
Mutations in superoxide dismutase 1 are associated with familial forms of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS).
A hexanucleotide repeat expansion in this gene is a common cause of both ALS and frontotemporal dementia.
Mutations in this gene are linked to inclusion body myopathy with early-onset Paget disease and frontotemporal dementia.
Associated with mitochondrial dysfunction leading to a spectrum of diseases including ALS and frontotemporal dementia.
Mutations in this gene are linked to autosomal recessive early-onset Parkinson's disease and oxidative stress response.
DCXR encodes dicarbonyl/L-xylulose reductase, an enzyme involved in the conversion of L-xylulose to xylitol in the pentose pathway.
LGALS1 encodes galectin-1, which can interact with beta-galactoside proteins involved in pentose sugar metabolism.
UGT1A1 encodes UDP-glucuronosyltransferase, which catalyzes the transfer of glucuronic acid to small lipophilic molecules.
UGT1A6 encodes another isoform of UDP-glucuronosyltransferase involved in glucuronidation processes.
UGT2B7 is another member of the UDP-glucuronosyltransferase family, involved in glucuronidation of diverse molecules.
RBKS encodes ribokinase, which converts ribose to ribose-5-phosphate, a crucial step in the pentose phosphate pathway.
ALDOA encodes aldolase A, which plays a role in the glycolysis and gluconeogenesis pathways, intersecting with the pentose phosphate pathway.
G6PD encodes glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase, the rate-limiting enzyme of the pentose phosphate pathway.
TKT encodes transketolase, an enzyme that catalyzes reactions in the non-oxidative phase of the pentose phosphate pathway.
PGD encodes 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase, involved in the oxidative branch of the pentose phosphate pathway.
IDH1 encodes isocitrate dehydrogenase, contributing to the production of NADPH, necessary for various steps in the pentose pathway.
TALDO1 encodes transaldolase 1, an enzyme involved in linking the pentose phosphate pathway with glycolysis.
PRPS1 encodes phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate synthetase 1, crucial for nucleotide synthesis which utilizes intermediates from the pentose phosphate pathway.
PRPS2 encodes a second isoform of phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate synthetase critical in the same pathway as PRPS1.
Encodes glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase, the enzyme that catalyzes the first step in the oxidative branch of the pentose phosphate pathway.
Encodes 6-phosphogluconolactonase, which hydrolyzes 6-phosphoglucono-δ-lactone to 6-phosphogluconate in the second step.
Encodes 6-phosphogluconate dehydrogenase, which catalyzes the oxidative decarboxylation of 6-phosphogluconate to ribulose-5-phosphate.
Encodes ribulose-5-phosphate epimerase, which converts ribulose-5-phosphate to xylulose-5-phosphate in the non-oxidative branch.
Encodes ribose-5-phosphate isomerase, which converts ribose-5-phosphate to ribulose-5-phosphate in the non-oxidative branch.
Encodes transketolase, an enzyme that catalyzes the transfer of two-carbon units in the non-oxidative branch of the pathway.
Encodes transaldolase 1, which is involved in the transfer of three-carbon units in the non-oxidative branch.
PEX1 encodes a protein involved in the import of peroxisomal matrix proteins.
PEX2 is essential for peroxisome biogenesis and function as it encodes a peroxin involved in peroxisomal membrane assembly.
PEX3 is required for the proper formation of pre-peroxisomal vesicles and peroxisomal membrane synthesis.
PEX5 encodes the peroxisomal targeting signal 1 (PTS1) receptor, crucial for importing matrix proteins into peroxisomes.
PEX6 functions in the recycling of the PTS1 receptor back to the cytosol, which is critical for continuous protein import into the peroxisome.
PEX7 encodes the PTS2 receptor, necessary for the import of PTS2-containing proteins into the peroxisomal matrix.
PEX10 is involved in peroxisomal matrix protein import and is part of the peroxisomal membrane protein complex.
PEX12 encodes a peroxin necessary for the import of matrix proteins and the stability of other peroxins.
PEX13 encodes a peroxisomal membrane protein required for the docking of PEX5-PTS1 and PEX7-PTS2 complexed proteins.
PEX14 acts as a docking factor for PTS receptors, facilitating the import of matrix proteins into peroxisomes.
PEX19 is involved in the early stages of peroxisomal membrane protein biogenesis by chaperoning and inserting peroxisomal membrane proteins.
ACOX1 encodes acyl-CoA oxidase, an enzyme that catalyzes the first step in fatty acid beta-oxidation within peroxisomes.
CAT encodes catalase, an enzyme that decomposes hydrogen peroxide within peroxisomes to prevent oxidative damage.
HSD17B4 encodes a bifunctional enzyme involved in the peroxisomal beta-oxidation of fatty acids.
PLP1 is implicated in peroxisomal membrane integrity and lipid metabolism, albeit indirectly connected to the peroxisomal processes.
Encodes the pertussis toxin subunit A, a key virulence factor of Bordetella pertussis.
Encodes pertactin, an adhesin protein that plays a crucial role in the adherence of Bordetella pertussis to host cells.
Encodes filamentous hemagglutinin, which mediates attachment of Bordetella pertussis to epithelial cells in the respiratory tract.
Encodes adenylate cyclase toxin, which helps Bordetella pertussis evade host immune responses.
Encodes tracheal cytotoxin, a peptidoglycan-derived cytotoxin that damages epithelial cells in the trachea.
Encodes dermonecrotic toxin, which causes tissue damage and is involved in Bordetella pertussis pathogenicity.
RAC1 is involved in the regulation of the actin cytoskeleton during phagosome formation.
ACTB encodes beta-actin, an essential component of the actin cytoskeleton required for phagosome formation and movement.
RAB5A regulates early stages of endocytosis and is crucial for the maturation of the early phagosome.
RAB7A is essential for the late stages of phagosome maturation and fusion with lysosomes.
EEA1 is an early endosomal antigen that facilitates the fusion of early phagosomes with early endosomes.
LAMP1 is a lysosomal associated membrane protein implicated in the fusion of phagosomes with lysosomes.
MTOR signaling influences phagosome formation and degradation.
PIK3C3 encoding the catalytic subunit of class III PI3-kinase is involved in autophagosome formation.
FYCO1 is involved in the transport of mature phagosomes along microtubules.
LYN, a Src-family tyrosine kinase, is involved in the signaling events during phagocytosis.
CD36 is a scavenger receptor that recognizes and binds to oxidized low-density lipoproteins and apoptotic cells, initiating phagocytosis.
ITGAM, also known as CD11b, is part of the Mac-1 integrin which is involved in the adhesion and phagocytosis of particles.
CLTC encodes clathrin, which is involved in vesicle formation and the endocytosis phase of phagosome formation.
VPS34 is a component of the PI3-kinase complex that regulates phagosome maturation.
CTSD encodes cathepsin D, a lysosomal protease that degrades contents within the phagosome.
MAP1LC3B (LC3) is recruited to phagophore membranes and is critical for autophagosome formation.
SQSTM1/p62 serves as a link between LC3 and ubiquitinated substrates, aiding in cargo recognition in autophagy.
CYBA encodes a component of the NADPH oxidase complex, necessary for the respiratory burst in phagosomes.
NOX2 is a subunit of the phagocyte NADPH oxidase that generates reactive oxygen species within the phagosome.
PAH encodes phenylalanine hydroxylase, the enzyme directly responsible for converting phenylalanine to tyrosine.
PTS encodes 6-pyruvoyltetrahydropterin synthase, required for the synthesis of tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4), a cofactor needed by phenylalanine hydroxylase.
GCH1 encodes GTP cyclohydrolase I, another enzyme necessary for the biosynthesis of tetrahydrobiopterin, crucial for phenylalanine hydroxylase activity.
QDPR encodes quinoid dihydropteridine reductase, which regenerates tetrahydrobiopterin from its oxidized form, sustaining phenylalanine hydroxylase function.
SPR encodes sepiapterin reductase, which is involved in the final steps of tetrahydrobiopterin biosynthesis, indirectly supporting phenylalanine metabolism.
DDC encodes aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase, which decarboxylates L-DOPA (a tyrosine derivative) to dopamine, playing an indirect role in the metabolic pathway connected to phenylalanine.
TH encodes tyrosine hydroxylase, which converts tyrosine (derived from phenylalanine) to L-DOPA, indirectly linking it to phenylalanine metabolism.
TAT encodes tyrosine aminotransferase, which transaminates tyrosine (a phenylalanine metabolite) to p-hydroxyphenylpyruvate, indicating a downstream role in phenylalanine catabolism.
HPD encodes 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvate dioxygenase, another enzyme in the tyrosine catabolic pathway, ultimately linking back to phenylalanine through tyrosine metabolism.
FAH encodes fumarylacetoacetate hydrolase, an enzyme of the tyrosine degradation pathway, indirectly connected to phenylalanine metabolism via tyrosine.
Encodes phenylalanine hydroxylase, which converts phenylalanine to tyrosine.
Encodes tyrosine hydroxylase, which catalyzes the conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA.
Encodes tryptophan hydroxylase 1, which converts tryptophan to 5-hydroxytryptophan in the serotonergic pathway.
Encodes tryptophan hydroxylase 2, which also converts tryptophan to 5-hydroxytryptophan, primarily in the brain.
Encodes aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase, which converts L-DOPA to dopamine and 5-hydroxytryptophan to serotonin.

Encodes pterin-4 alpha-carbinolamine dehydratase/dimerization cofactor of hepatocyte nuclear factor 1 alpha which is involved in the regeneration of tetrahydrobiopterin, a cofactor for phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan hydroxylases.
Encodes GTP cyclohydrolase 1, a critical enzyme in the biosynthesis of tetrahydrobiopterin, a cofactor required by phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan hydroxylases.
Encodes 6-pyruvoyl-tetrahydropterin synthase, another enzyme involved in the biosynthesis of tetrahydrobiopterin.
Encodes pterin-4 alpha-carbinolamine dehydratase, another enzyme in the tetrahydrobiopterin regeneration pathway important for phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan hydroxylation.
Encodes the catalytic subunit of phosphoinositide 3-kinase which is crucial for the phosphorylation of phosphatidylinositols.
Encodes a serine/threonine-specific protein kinase that is a downstream effector in the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase pathway.
Acts as a phosphatase to dephosphorylate PIP3, opposing the action of PI3K and regulating cell growth and survival.
Encodes SHIP1, an inositol polyphosphate-5-phosphatase that dephosphorylates PIP3 to PIP2, modulating PI3K signaling.
Encodes the regulatory subunit of PI3K, necessary for the proper function and regulation of the PI3K enzyme.
Encodes phospholipase C gamma 1, which hydrolyzes PIP2 into IP3 and DAG, key second messengers in cellular signaling.
Encodes inositol-trisphosphate 3-kinase B, which phosphorylates IP3 to produce IP4, involved in calcium signaling.
Encodes phosphatidylinositol 4-kinase alpha, responsible for phosphorylating PI to produce PI4P, a precursor for PIP2.
Encodes protein kinase C alpha, which is activated by DAG, a product of PIP2 hydrolysis by PLC enzymes.
Encodes diacylglycerol kinase alpha, which phosphorylates DAG to produce PA, regulating intracellular signaling.
PLD1 encodes for phospholipase D1, a key enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine to generate phosphatidic acid, an important signaling molecule.
PLD2 encodes for phospholipase D2, another isoform that also catalyzes the production of phosphatidic acid, thus playing a crucial role in signaling.
RHOA encodes for a small GTPase that activates PLD enzymes, thereby integrating into the PLD signaling pathway.
ARF1 encodes for ADP-ribosylation factor 1, a small GTPase that regulates PLD activity.
PKC (Protein Kinase C) can phosphorylate and activate PLD enzymes, linking it to the PLD signaling pathway.
GNAQ encodes for a G protein subunit that can activate PLD through G protein-coupled receptor signaling.
SRC tyrosine kinase can phosphorylate PLD2, promoting its enzymatic activity.
PI4KA encodes phosphatidylinositol 4-kinase alpha, an enzyme that interacts with PLD, influencing its localization and function.
PLCG1 encodes phospholipase C gamma 1 which can produce diacylglycerol (DAG), a molecule that indirectly activates protein kinase C (PKC) and consequently PLD.
VPS45 encodes for a vacuolar protein sorting protein that has been linked to the regulation of PLD activity.
Encodes a component of the phosphonate transport system enabling uptake of phosphonates.
Encodes a phosphonate-binding protein essential for phosphonate transport.
Encodes a permease, part of the phosphonate transport system.
Encodes a transcriptional regulator impacting expression of phosphonate metabolism genes.
Encodes a protein involved in phosphonate degradation pathways.
Encodes a protein required for phosphonate catabolism.
Encodes a subunit in the enzymatic complex that degrades phosphonates.
Encodes a protein critical for breaking the C-P bond in phosphonates.
Plays a structural and functional role in the phosphonate-degrading enzyme complex.
Associated with the regulation or processing of phosphonate compounds.
Encodes rhodopsin, a light-sensitive receptor protein involved in phototransduction in rod cells.
Encodes the alpha subunit of transducin, which activates the phototransduction cascade in rod photoreceptors.
Encodes the alpha subunit of transducin specific to cone photoreceptors, playing a crucial role in phototransduction.
Encodes the alpha subunit of cyclic GMP phosphodiesterase, a key enzyme in the phototransduction pathway in rod cells.
Encodes the beta subunit of cyclic GMP phosphodiesterase which is essential for the phototransduction process in rod cells.
Encodes the alpha-prime subunit of cone-specific cyclic GMP phosphodiesterase, important for cone phototransduction.
Encodes guanylate cyclase 2D, which helps restore cGMP levels after phototransduction activation in photoreceptors.
Encodes calcium-binding protein 4, modulating calcium signaling in phototransduction.
Encodes arrestin 3, involved in deactivating cone photopigments in the phototransduction process.
Encodes S-antigen protein, also known as arrestin, involved in deactivating rhodopsin in rod cells, thus stopping the phototransduction signal.
Encodes the alpha subunit of the cyclic nucleotide-gated channel, a crucial component for the phototransduction cascade in rod cells.
Encodes the beta subunit of the cyclic nucleotide-gated channel in rod cells, essential for the phototransduction process.
Encodes the alpha subunit of the cyclic nucleotide-gated channel in cone photoreceptors, critical for phototransduction.
Encodes the beta subunit of the cone cyclic nucleotide-gated channel, playing a vital role in the cone phototransduction pathway.
Encodes integrin αIIb, a key component of the platelet membrane glycoprotein complex involved in platelet aggregation.
Encodes integrin β3, which forms a receptor complex with integrin αIIb essential for platelet adhesion and clot formation.
Encodes the platelet membrane glycoprotein Ib alpha chain, which is part of the receptor for von Willebrand factor involved in platelet adhesion.
Encodes glycoprotein Ib beta chain, a component of the von Willebrand factor receptor complex crucial for platelet adhesion.
Encodes glycoprotein IX, part of the GP Ib-IX-V complex involved in platelet adhesion.
Encodes von Willebrand factor, which mediates the adhesion of platelets to damaged blood vessels.
Encodes glycoprotein VI, a platelet collagen receptor involved in collagen-induced platelet activation.
Encodes a C-type lectin domain family member, CLEC-2, involved in platelet activation through the podoplanin receptor.
Encodes filamin A, which is involved in platelet cytoskeleton organization and adhesion.
Encodes cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1), which is involved in the synthesis of thromboxane A2, a promoter of platelet aggregation.
Encodes the thromboxane A2 receptor, which mediates platelet aggregation and vasoconstriction.
Encodes cytosolic phospholipase A2, which releases arachidonic acid for thromboxane A2 synthesis in platelet activation.
Encodes protein kinase C alpha, which is involved in signal transduction pathways leading to platelet activation.
Encodes phospholipase C beta 2, which generates second messengers leading to calcium mobilization and platelet activation.
Encodes a non-receptor tyrosine kinase that plays a role in the signaling pathways of platelet activation.
Encodes spleen tyrosine kinase, essential for signal transduction in platelet activation through the ITAM-mediated pathway.
Encodes the linker for activation of T cells protein, which is involved in immune receptor signaling in platelets.
Encodes the thrombin receptor, which plays a central role in thrombin-induced platelet aggregation and activation.
Encodes platelet factor 4, a protein released during platelet activation and involved in coagulation.
Encodes pro-platelet basic protein, also known as CXCL7, which is involved in platelet activation and chemotaxis.
ALAS1 is involved in the first step of heme biosynthesis, which is critical for porphyrin metabolism.
ALAS2, similar to ALAS1, catalyzes the first step in the heme biosynthetic pathway, essential for porphyrin metabolism.
UROS catalyzes the cyclization of hydroxymethylbilane, a key step in porphyrin metabolism.
UROD is responsible for decarboxylating uroporphyrinogen to coproporphyrinogen in the porphyrin metabolism pathway.
CPOX converts coproporphyrinogen III to protoporphyrinogen IX, an essential step in porphyrin biosynthesis.
PPOX oxidizes protoporphyrinogen IX to protoporphyrin IX, a crucial reaction in porphyrin metabolism.
FECH inserts iron into protoporphyrin IX to form heme, a final step in porphyrin and heme biosynthesis.
ABCG2 transports porphyrins and chlorophyll derivatives, playing a protective role in their metabolism.
BLVRA is involved in the reduction of biliverdin to bilirubin, a step in the heme degradation pathway linked to porphyrin metabolism.

HMOX1 catalyzes the degradation of heme to biliverdin, linking to porphyrin metabolism.
HMOX2, like HMOX1, degrades heme into biliverdin, iron, and carbon monoxide, playing a role in porphyrin metabolism.
UROG (uroporphyrinogen III accumulative) is implicated in the regulation of porphyrin metabolism pathways.
GCH1 is indirectly involved by functioning in the biosynthesis of tetrahydrobiopterin, a cofactor for aromatic amino acid hydroxylase enzymes impacting porphyrin metabolism.
ChlG (Chlorophyll synthase) catalyzes the esterification of chlorophyllide to chlorophyll, a key step in chlorophyll metabolism.
ChlL, part of the light-independent protochlorophyllide reductase complex, is essential for converting protochlorophyllide to chlorophyllide.
ChlN works alongside ChlL in the light-independent protochlorophyllide reductase complex for chlorophyll biosynthesis.
ChlB also participates in the light-independent reduction of protochlorophyllide to chlorophyllide, which is a crucial process in chlorophyll biosynthesis.
HEMA1 is a glutamyl-tRNA reductase involved in the initial step of chlorophyll biosynthesis, directly contributing to chlorophyll metabolism.
CHLH codes for the H subunit of magnesium chelatase, which catalyzes the insertion of Mg2+ into protoporphyrin IX to form Mg-protoporphyrin IX in chlorophyll biosynthesis.
Catalyzes the rate-limiting step in bile acid synthesis from cholesterol.
Regulates the balance of bile acids by hydroxylating sterols in the production pathway.
Involved in the alternative pathway of bile acid biosynthesis by catalyzing hydroxylation of sterol intermediates.
Encodes 5-beta reductase which is crucial for bile acid synthesis by reducing the double bond in intermediates.
Encodes 3-beta-hydroxy-delta5-C27-steroid dehydrogenase involved in the initial steps of bile acid synthesis.
Catalyzes the conjugation of bile acids with amino acids, an essential step for bile acid functionality.
Transports bile acids into hepatocytes for further processing and excretion.
Encodes the sodium/taurocholate cotransporting polypeptide critical for hepatic uptake of bile acids.
Involved in the glucuronidation of bile acids, aiding in their solubility and excretion.
Encodes the bile salt export pump essential for bile acid secretion into the bile canaliculi.
Mutations in BTK lead to X-linked agammaglobulinemia, a primary immunodeficiency characterized by the absence of mature B cells.
Mutations in ADA cause adenosine deaminase deficiency, leading to severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID).
Mutations in IL2RG result in X-linked SCID, which is characterized by a defect in the common gamma chain of several interleukin receptors.
RAG1 mutations disrupt V(D)J recombination, leading to SCID due to a failure in lymphocyte development.
Like RAG1, RAG2 mutations impede V(D)J recombination, causing SCID because of impaired lymphocyte development.
Mutations in DCLRE1C, encoding Artemis, cause SCID due to the failure in DNA repair during V(D)J recombination.
Mutations in FOXP3 cause IPEX syndrome, a primary immunodeficiency characterized by immune dysregulation, polyendocrinopathy, and enteropathy.
Mutations in TAP1 affect peptide transport, leading to bare lymphocyte syndrome type I, a type of primary immunodeficiency.
Like TAP1, TAP2 mutations disrupt peptide transport and antigen presentation, causing bare lymphocyte syndrome type I.
Mutations in CD40LG result in X-linked hyper IgM syndrome, a primary immunodeficiency where B cell class switching is impaired.
Mutations in AIRE cause autoimmune polyendocrinopathy-candidiasis-ectodermal dystrophy (APECED), leading to immune dysregulation.
Mutations in JAK3 lead to autosomal recessive SCID, as JAK3 is crucial for signaling through the common gamma chain in cytokine receptors.
Mutations in NCF1 cause chronic granulomatous disease (CGD), affecting the ability of phagocytes to produce reactive oxygen species.
NCF2 mutations also result in CGD by impairing the NADPH oxidase complex in phagocytes.
Mutations in CYBA lead to CGD due to dysfunctional NADPH oxidase complex in phagocytes.
Mutations in CYBB, encoding gp91phox, cause the X-linked form of CGD by disrupting the NADPH oxidase complex.
Mutations in CGD affect the NADPH oxidase complex, causing chronic granulomatous disease.
Encodes the prion protein (PrP), which misfolds to form pathological prions.
Encodes doppel, a prion-like protein, which has similar structural features to PrP.
Encodes the prion protein testis-specific (Prt), which may interact with prion protein gene products.
Involved in amyloid precursor protein processing, which can interact with prion proteins.
Encodes progranulin, shown to modulate prion disease pathogenesis in certain models.
Encodes tau protein, which may co-aggregate with misfolded prion proteins.
Encodes presenilin 1, part of the gamma-secretase complex involved in proteolytic processing of prion protein.
Encodes presenilin 2, similar to PSEN1 playing a role in prion protein processing.
Encodes a molecular chaperone that has been implicated in the refolding of misfolded prion proteins.
Encodes DNA methyltransferase 1, which modulates the expression of prion protein gene.
Encodes the progesterone receptor which is directly involved in mediating the effects of progesterone in oocyte maturation.
Plays a key role in the MAP kinase pathway, which is activated by progesterone during oocyte maturation.
Essential for the resumption of meiosis in oocytes, acting downstream of progesterone signaling.
Activates MAPK1/ERK2 pathway crucial for oocyte maturation in response to progesterone.
Involved in the regulation of cAMP levels which is modulated by progesterone signaling in oocyte maturation.
Catalytic subunit of protein kinase A that mediates some of the downstream effects of progesterone via cAMP signaling.
Tubulin required for microtubule formation, which is necessary for spindle assembly in oocyte maturation.
Activates MAP kinases, including MAPK1, and is part of the signal transduction pathway modulated by progesterone.
Also known as ERK1, is involved in the MAPK cascade activated during oocyte maturation by progesterone.
Regulatory subunit of protein phosphatase 2A, which has essential roles in the dephosphorylation processes during oocyte maturation influenced by progesterone.
Encodes prolactin, the main ligand that activates the prolactin receptor signaling pathway.
Encodes the prolactin receptor, which binds prolactin to initiate intracellular signaling cascades.
Encodes a tyrosine kinase that is activated by the prolactin receptor and initiates downstream signaling.
Encodes a transcription factor activated by JAK2 in response to prolactin, facilitating gene transcription.
Encodes another transcription factor activated by JAK2, working in parallel with STAT5A in the prolactin pathway.
Encodes an insulin receptor substrate that mediates prolactin-induced metabolic signaling.
Encodes a catalytic subunit of phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K), involved in prolactin-induced PI3K/AKT signaling.
Encodes a serine/threonine kinase activated by PI3K, involved in the proliferative and anti-apoptotic effects of prolactin.
Encodes a mitogen-activated protein kinase involved in prolactin-induced MAPK/ERK signaling for cell growth.
Encodes a suppressor of cytokine signaling protein that negatively regulates the prolactin signaling pathway.
Encodes another suppressor of cytokine signaling protein that inhibits the prolactin-JAK-STAT pathway.
Encodes an adaptor protein linking the prolactin receptor to the MAPK signaling pathway.
Encodes a signaling adaptor that participates in linking activated prolactin receptors to intracellular signaling pathways.
Encodes an adaptor protein that associates with the prolactin receptor complex, facilitating signal transduction.
Encodes cyclin D1, which is transcriptionally regulated by prolactin signaling to control cell cycle progression.
ACSS2 encodes an enzyme that converts acetate and CoA to acetyl-CoA, which is a key intermediate in propanoate metabolism.
ACACA encodes acetyl-CoA carboxylase, which catalyzes the first step of fatty acid biosynthesis and plays a role in propanoate metabolism.
MUT encodes methylmalonyl-CoA mutase, which is directly involved in the catabolism of propanoate by converting methylmalonyl-CoA to succinyl-CoA.
PCCA encodes a subunit of propionyl-CoA carboxylase, which converts propionyl-CoA to methylmalonyl-CoA in propanoate metabolism.
PCCB encodes another subunit of propionyl-CoA carboxylase, essential for the conversion of propionyl-CoA to methylmalonyl-CoA.
ACAT1 encodes acetyl-CoA acetyltransferase 1, which is involved in both ketone body and propanoate metabolism.
SUCLA2 encodes a subunit of succinate-CoA ligase, which is part of the TCA cycle that interfaces with propanoate metabolism.
SUCLG1 encodes another subunit of succinate-CoA ligase, integral to the TCA cycle, and hence involved in propanoate metabolism.
ALDH6A1 encodes an enzyme that participates in the oxidation of propanal to propanoate in propanoate metabolism.
ECHDC1 encodes a mitochondrial enoyl-CoA hydratase, involved in the metabolism of short-chain fatty acids like propanoate.
Mutations in TP53 are frequently observed in prostate cancer, impacting cell cycle regulation and apoptosis.
Loss of PTEN function is common in prostate cancer and leads to uncontrolled cell growth and survival.
The Androgen Receptor (AR) is critical for prostate cancer development and progression through its role in androgen signaling.
Germline mutations in BRCA2 increase the risk of developing prostate cancer due to its role in DNA repair.
ERG gene fusions are frequently detected in prostate cancer and contribute to oncogenesis.
Overexpression of MYC is associated with prostate cancer and promotes cancer cell proliferation and survival.
NKX3-1 is a prostate-specific tumor suppressor gene that is often inactivated in prostate cancer.
AKT1 activation is involved in prostate cancer progression through the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway.
EZH2 overexpression contributes to prostate cancer progression by epigenetically silencing tumor suppressor genes.
Mutations in SPOP are found in a subset of prostate cancers and affect ubiquitination and protein degradation processes.
TMPRSS2 gene fusions, particularly with ERG, are common in prostate cancer and drive oncogenic processes.
FOXA1 mutations and overexpression are implicated in prostate cancer, influencing AR signaling and chromatin remodeling.
ATM mutations lead to defects in DNA damage response and are associated with an increased risk of prostate cancer.
Loss of RB1 function disrupts cell cycle control and is frequently observed in advanced prostate cancer.
Germline mutations in HOXB13 are linked to hereditary prostate cancer risk.

PSMB5 is a beta subunit of the 20S proteasome, crucial for its role in degrading misfolded proteins.
PSMB6 encodes a beta subunit within the 20S core proteasome that contributes to its proteolytic activities.

PSMB10 is a beta subunit gene of the immunoproteasome, playing a role in antigen processing.

PSMD10 is a non-ATPase subunit gene involved in the 19S regulatory particle, affecting proteasome activity.

RET proto-oncogene mutations and rearrangements (RET/PTC) are frequently involved in the development of thyroid cancers, especially medullary thyroid carcinoma.
